00:04:10.610 --> 00:04:12.990
Let's just take a step back for a moment

00:04:12.990 --> 00:04:15.500
and remind everybody
what we're talking about.

00:04:15.500 --> 00:04:19.240
We're talking about an
endogenous, meaning within us,

00:04:19.240 --> 00:04:21.890
rhythm that we call the circadian rhythm.

00:04:21.890 --> 00:04:25.230
The circadian rhythm is a 24 hour rhythm

00:04:25.230 --> 00:04:28.340
in all sorts of functions.

00:04:28.340 --> 00:04:30.780
The most prominent one is a rhythm

00:04:30.780 --> 00:04:34.280
in our feelings of
wakefulness and sleepiness.

00:04:34.280 --> 00:04:35.920
So believe it or not,

00:04:35.920 --> 00:04:38.360
the experiment has been
done throughout history,

00:04:38.360 --> 00:04:39.760
not often, but it's been done

00:04:39.760 --> 00:04:42.130
where people would go down into a cave

00:04:42.130 --> 00:04:45.560
and will exist in constant
darkness for some period of time.

00:04:45.560 --> 00:04:46.393
There are also cases

00:04:46.393 --> 00:04:47.730
where people have been in constant light

00:04:47.730 --> 00:04:49.390
for some period of time.

00:04:49.390 --> 00:04:51.130
But because people can close their eyes,

00:04:51.130 --> 00:04:53.200
it's actually easier to do the experiment

00:04:53.200 --> 00:04:54.610
where you're in constant darkness

00:04:54.610 --> 00:04:57.320
to address the question
of what is the endogenous,

00:04:57.320 --> 00:04:59.720
meaning, the internal
rhythm that we all have.

00:04:59.720 --> 00:05:03.410
And it turns out we all have
this rhythm of about 24 hours,

00:05:03.410 --> 00:05:05.170
although it's not exactly 24 hours.

00:05:05.170 --> 00:05:10.030
Meaning, every 24 hours
your body temperature

00:05:10.030 --> 00:05:13.050
goes from low to high and
back down to low again.

00:05:13.050 --> 00:05:15.090
And it takes 24 hours for that to repeat.

00:05:15.090 --> 00:05:19.643
Not 18, not six, 24 plus
or minus a couple hours.

00:05:20.610 --> 00:05:23.870
You also have a rhythm in
sleepiness and wakefulness

00:05:23.870 --> 00:05:24.790
that correlates with that.

00:05:24.790 --> 00:05:28.280
We tend to be sleepy as
our temperature is falling,

00:05:28.280 --> 00:05:33.280
getting lower, and we tend
to be more awake or waking

00:05:33.300 --> 00:05:35.840
when our temperature is increasing.

00:05:35.840 --> 00:05:37.440
This is a biological fact.

00:05:37.440 --> 00:05:39.940
It is right down to our DNA.

00:05:39.940 --> 00:05:42.410
We actually have genes in
every single one of our cells

00:05:42.410 --> 00:05:46.550
that ensure that every cell
is on this 24 hour-ish rhythm,

00:05:46.550 --> 00:05:47.723
close to 24 hours.

00:05:49.210 --> 00:05:52.160
We have a clock over
the roof of our mouth,

00:05:52.160 --> 00:05:55.210
a group of neurons called
the suprachiasmatic nucleus.

00:05:56.180 --> 00:05:59.010
That clock generates a 24 hour rhythm.

00:05:59.010 --> 00:06:02.800
And that clock is in-trained,
meaning it is matched,

00:06:02.800 --> 00:06:04.950
to the external light-dark cycle,

00:06:04.950 --> 00:06:08.140
which is no surprise, 24 hours.

00:06:08.140 --> 00:06:10.550
Spinning of the earth takes 24 hours.

00:06:10.550 --> 00:06:15.060
So, our cells, our organs,

00:06:15.060 --> 00:06:17.670
our wakefulness, our temperature,

00:06:17.670 --> 00:06:21.720
but also our metabolism,
our immune system, our mood,

00:06:21.720 --> 00:06:25.610
all of that is tethered to
the outside light-dark cycle.

00:06:25.610 --> 00:06:29.030
And if we are living our
life in a perfect way,

00:06:29.030 --> 00:06:31.300
where we wake up in the morning,

00:06:31.300 --> 00:06:34.660
and we view sunlight as
it crosses the horizon,

00:06:34.660 --> 00:06:37.280
and then by evening, we
catch a little sunlight

00:06:38.350 --> 00:06:41.020
and then at night we're
in complete darkness,

00:06:41.020 --> 00:06:43.240
we will be more or less perfectly matched

00:06:43.240 --> 00:06:45.893
to the external or
ambient light-dark cycle.

00:06:46.900 --> 00:06:48.810
Very few of us do that

00:06:48.810 --> 00:06:51.800
because of these things that
we call artificial lights,

00:06:51.800 --> 00:06:55.110
and this other thing that
we call life demands.

00:06:55.110 --> 00:06:57.210
So today we're going to talk about

00:06:57.210 --> 00:07:00.060
when we get pulled away from that rhythm.

00:07:00.060 --> 00:07:03.290
Now you may immediately be thinking,

00:07:03.290 --> 00:07:05.120
well, I've heard there are night owls

00:07:05.120 --> 00:07:07.790
and there are mornings larks,
they're sometimes called

00:07:07.790 --> 00:07:09.580
and their genetic polymorphisms,

00:07:09.580 --> 00:07:11.050
that's just a fancy name for

00:07:11.050 --> 00:07:13.590
genetic variations that make
some people want to wake up early

00:07:13.590 --> 00:07:14.647
and other people want to stay up late

00:07:14.647 --> 00:07:16.490
and teens want to sleep in more.

00:07:16.490 --> 00:07:18.390
Sure, that's all true.

00:07:18.390 --> 00:07:20.830
That's all true regardless
of what names we give those.

00:07:20.830 --> 00:07:23.730
However, there's no escaping the fact

00:07:23.730 --> 00:07:26.170
that human beings are a diurnal species.

00:07:26.170 --> 00:07:28.710
We were designed, literally,

00:07:28.710 --> 00:07:30.840
our cells and the circuits of our body

00:07:30.840 --> 00:07:34.250
were constructed to be
awake during the daytime

00:07:34.250 --> 00:07:35.600
and asleep at night.

00:07:35.600 --> 00:07:36.600
How do I know that?

00:07:36.600 --> 00:07:39.160
Well, I wasn't consulted
at the design phase,

00:07:39.160 --> 00:07:43.020
but I'm certain of that
because many studies have shown

00:07:43.020 --> 00:07:47.340
that when we deviate too
far from a diurnal schedule

00:07:47.340 --> 00:07:50.720
and we try and become
nocturnal, we can pull it off,

00:07:50.720 --> 00:07:53.560
but serious health effects,
both mental and physical,

00:07:53.560 --> 00:07:55.270
start to arise.

00:07:55.270 --> 00:07:57.060
I'm not going to spend much of today

00:07:57.060 --> 00:07:59.220
talking about all the
negative effects of jet lag

00:07:59.220 --> 00:08:00.970
I'll talk a little bit about it,

00:08:00.970 --> 00:08:02.630
or the negative effects of shift work,

00:08:02.630 --> 00:08:04.050
or trying to scare you

00:08:04.050 --> 00:08:06.920
by telling you about the quite valid data

00:08:06.920 --> 00:08:11.770
around depression, amnesia,

00:08:11.770 --> 00:08:13.980
dementia, all the terrible
things that happen

00:08:13.980 --> 00:08:15.060
when you're not sleeping well,

00:08:15.060 --> 00:08:16.870
rather I'd like to
focus on what you can do

00:08:16.870 --> 00:08:18.670
and arm you with tools.

00:08:18.670 --> 00:08:21.840
So let's talk about that
perfect schedule for a moment.

00:08:21.840 --> 00:08:23.550
And then let's talk about jet lag

00:08:23.550 --> 00:08:26.200
and what jet lag really represents

00:08:26.200 --> 00:08:30.200
and how to push back on jet
lag, shift your clock faster,

00:08:30.200 --> 00:08:33.550
and escape some of the severe bad things

00:08:33.550 --> 00:08:34.910
that can happen with jet lag.

00:08:34.910 --> 00:08:36.700
Including just feeling miserable

00:08:36.700 --> 00:08:38.890
when you're traveling
for work or vacation.

00:08:38.890 --> 00:08:41.030
So what is the perfect day?

00:08:41.030 --> 00:08:43.070
What does that look
like from our circadian

00:08:43.070 --> 00:08:45.340
sleep-wakefulness standpoint?

00:08:45.340 --> 00:08:47.930
I'm about to summarize what I've said in

00:08:47.930 --> 00:08:50.790
the three previous podcast episodes,

00:08:50.790 --> 00:08:53.593
as well as now countless Instagram posts.

00:08:55.190 --> 00:08:56.230
Here's the deal.

00:08:56.230 --> 00:09:01.230
You basically want to get as
much light, ideally sunlight,

00:09:02.370 --> 00:09:05.090
but as much light into your eyes

00:09:05.090 --> 00:09:07.340
during the period of each 24 hour cycle

00:09:07.340 --> 00:09:10.830
when you want to be awake,
when you want to be alert.

00:09:10.830 --> 00:09:14.440
And you want to get as
little light into your eyes

00:09:15.340 --> 00:09:17.167
at the times of that 24 hour cycle

00:09:17.167 --> 00:09:20.923
when you want to be asleep
or drowsy and falling asleep.

00:09:22.030 --> 00:09:23.200
How much is enough?

00:09:23.200 --> 00:09:25.700
Well, you don't want to go so high

00:09:25.700 --> 00:09:27.670
with the light exposure
that you damage your eyes

00:09:27.670 --> 00:09:30.090
because as many of you
have heard me say before,

00:09:30.090 --> 00:09:32.460
the eyes are actually
two pieces of your brain,

00:09:32.460 --> 00:09:33.380
your central nervous system

00:09:33.380 --> 00:09:35.120
that were extruded out of your skull.

00:09:35.120 --> 00:09:38.240
And as pieces of the central
nervous system, aka your brain,

00:09:38.240 --> 00:09:40.300
they will not regenerate.

00:09:40.300 --> 00:09:42.230
At least right now, the
technologies don't exist

00:09:42.230 --> 00:09:43.630
to regenerate those neurons in humans

00:09:43.630 --> 00:09:45.450
you do not want to damage them.

00:09:45.450 --> 00:09:46.820
So what is too bright?

00:09:46.820 --> 00:09:49.400
Well, when it's painful to look at.

00:09:49.400 --> 00:09:50.760
When you have to blink or close your eyes

00:09:50.760 --> 00:09:51.593
in order to bear it.

00:09:51.593 --> 00:09:54.780
So please don't look
at very bright lights,

00:09:54.780 --> 00:09:58.463
so painful that they're likely
going to damage your eyes.

00:09:59.440 --> 00:10:02.540
However, if you get up in the morning,

00:10:02.540 --> 00:10:06.010
and it's still dark out
and you want to be awake,

00:10:06.010 --> 00:10:09.370
you would be wise to turn
on artificial lights,

00:10:09.370 --> 00:10:10.590
in particular, overhead lights

00:10:10.590 --> 00:10:12.130
for reasons I've discussed previously.

00:10:12.130 --> 00:10:13.410
But those overhead lights will

00:10:13.410 --> 00:10:14.920
optimally trigger the neurons,

00:10:14.920 --> 00:10:17.580
these melanopsin cells in the retina

00:10:17.580 --> 00:10:20.230
that will activate your circadian clock.

00:10:20.230 --> 00:10:23.850
When the sun comes out,
even if there's cloud cover,

00:10:23.850 --> 00:10:26.070
the sun does come out every day

00:10:26.070 --> 00:10:29.480
regardless of where you live,
unless you live in a cave.

00:10:29.480 --> 00:10:30.313
People have said to me,

00:10:30.313 --> 00:10:32.520
well, I live in an area where
I can't really see the sun.

00:10:32.520 --> 00:10:34.193
Well, the sun is there,

00:10:35.170 --> 00:10:37.120
it might be hiding behind clouds,

00:10:37.120 --> 00:10:39.100
unless it's very very dark where you live

00:10:39.100 --> 00:10:41.490
like Scandinavia in the depths of winter

00:10:41.490 --> 00:10:44.270
in which case you might
want some artificial light.

00:10:44.270 --> 00:10:47.060
Get some sunlight in
your eyes when you can.

00:10:47.060 --> 00:10:49.960
Here's the deal with
sunlight and artificial light

00:10:49.960 --> 00:10:51.810
that I have not discussed previously.

00:10:53.380 --> 00:10:56.060
A lot of photon energy,

00:10:56.060 --> 00:11:00.150
a high amount of lux, L-U-X,
comes through even cloud cover.

00:11:00.150 --> 00:11:03.430
A good number to shoot
for as a rule of thumb,

00:11:03.430 --> 00:11:04.890
is to try and get exposure

00:11:04.890 --> 00:11:09.890
to at least 100,000 lux before 9:00 AM.

00:11:11.049 --> 00:11:14.380
10:00 AM maybe, but before 9:00 AM

00:11:14.380 --> 00:11:19.380
assuming you're waking up
sometime between five and 8:00 AM.

00:11:19.520 --> 00:11:21.380
Okay, so get 100,000 lux.

00:11:21.380 --> 00:11:23.100
Now you do not, I want to repeat,

00:11:23.100 --> 00:11:26.010
you do not want to stare at a 200,000 lux

00:11:26.010 --> 00:11:28.570
or a 100,000 lux light.

00:11:28.570 --> 00:11:29.823
It's very, very bright.

00:11:30.850 --> 00:11:34.020
The mechanism of circadian clock setting

00:11:34.020 --> 00:11:35.830
and this is very important,

00:11:35.830 --> 00:11:37.810
the mechanism of circadian clock setting

00:11:37.810 --> 00:11:40.280
involves these neurons in your eye

00:11:40.280 --> 00:11:41.730
that send electrical signals

00:11:41.730 --> 00:11:44.140
to this clock above the roof of your mouth

00:11:44.140 --> 00:11:47.990
and that system sums,
meaning it adds photons,

00:11:47.990 --> 00:11:49.800
it's a very slow system.

00:11:49.800 --> 00:11:51.780
So let's say that I wake up

00:11:51.780 --> 00:11:55.700
and I look at my computer screen
briefly or my phone screen.

00:11:55.700 --> 00:11:57.850
That's probably 500 to 1,000 lux.

00:11:57.850 --> 00:12:00.610
If I were to look at
that for a full minute,

00:12:00.610 --> 00:12:02.840
I would get that photon energy

00:12:02.840 --> 00:12:04.870
transferred into electrical
energy of neurons

00:12:04.870 --> 00:12:06.970
and it would be communicated
to my circadian clock.

00:12:06.970 --> 00:12:08.960
However, the signal that it's morning

00:12:08.960 --> 00:12:12.360
will not have registered
with the circadian clock

00:12:12.360 --> 00:12:17.030
unless I looked at that for
a hundred minutes or more,

00:12:17.030 --> 00:12:17.920
so 100,000.

00:12:17.920 --> 00:12:20.910
Now the problem is if you
wake up at eight o'clock,

00:12:20.910 --> 00:12:23.780
you're not going to get enough
light from artificial light

00:12:23.780 --> 00:12:26.040
before you reach what's called
the circadian dead zone.

00:12:26.040 --> 00:12:29.960
So you have this opportunity
before 9:00 AM, maybe 10:00 AM

00:12:29.960 --> 00:12:32.080
to capture enough photons,

00:12:32.080 --> 00:12:34.760
and you have to do it with your eyes.

00:12:34.760 --> 00:12:36.450
I've discussed why that's important

00:12:36.450 --> 00:12:38.050
in previous episodes of the podcast,

00:12:38.050 --> 00:12:39.350
we have to do it with your eyes.

00:12:39.350 --> 00:12:41.550
There is no extra ocular photo reception.

00:12:41.550 --> 00:12:44.280
This is not about vitamin D in your skin.

00:12:44.280 --> 00:12:46.450
This is about setting your circadian clock

00:12:46.450 --> 00:12:48.810
which is paramount for
mental and physical health.

00:12:48.810 --> 00:12:50.240
So here we're talking
about trying to get that

00:12:50.240 --> 00:12:52.730
at least 100,000 photons
but not all at once,

00:12:52.730 --> 00:12:56.350
but you got to get them before
9:00 AM-ish, maybe 10:00 AM.

00:12:56.350 --> 00:12:57.183
So what do you do?

00:12:57.183 --> 00:12:58.300
You go outside.

00:12:58.300 --> 00:13:01.250
If you want to get nerdy
about this quantitative,

00:13:01.250 --> 00:13:03.820
you could download a
free app like Light Meter

00:13:03.820 --> 00:13:06.300
and take a look around
your house with Light Meter

00:13:06.300 --> 00:13:08.890
and you'll notice that
even bright overhead lights

00:13:08.890 --> 00:13:13.260
are only emitting about
4,000 or 5,000 lux.

00:13:13.260 --> 00:13:15.390
It's going to take a long while
of looking at those lights

00:13:15.390 --> 00:13:17.840
with eyes open in order to
set your circadian clock

00:13:17.840 --> 00:13:20.190
and tell your brain and
body that it's morning.

00:13:21.040 --> 00:13:23.450
Going outside even on a cloudy day

00:13:24.410 --> 00:13:26.540
could be 7,000, 10,000 lux.

00:13:26.540 --> 00:13:29.070
It's really remarkable how bright it is,

00:13:29.070 --> 00:13:31.010
meaning how much photon
energy is coming through.

00:13:31.010 --> 00:13:34.870
So try and get 100,000
lux before that 9:00 AM.

00:13:34.870 --> 00:13:35.980
Now, if you can't do that

00:13:35.980 --> 00:13:37.840
because you live in an area of the world

00:13:37.840 --> 00:13:40.410
where it's just not bright enough.

00:13:40.410 --> 00:13:43.900
Some people have sent me
pictures from Northern England.

00:13:43.900 --> 00:13:45.990
It's just not bright enough in winter.

00:13:45.990 --> 00:13:49.870
Then sure, you can resort
to using artificial lights

00:13:49.870 --> 00:13:52.400
in order to get enough photons.

00:13:52.400 --> 00:13:55.850
And I'm putting out this
100,000 lux number as a target

00:13:55.850 --> 00:13:57.653
to get each day before 9:00 AM.

00:13:59.160 --> 00:14:01.440
You can in theory, get it
all from artificial lights,

00:14:01.440 --> 00:14:03.500
but there are some special
qualities about sunlight

00:14:03.500 --> 00:14:05.670
that make sunlight the better stimulus.

00:14:05.670 --> 00:14:08.733
First of all, it's free
if it's available outside.

