But I can't emphasize this enough

00:14:55.310 --> 00:14:57.460
that light has to be captured and summed

00:14:57.460 --> 00:14:59.350
before you enter the circadian dead zone

00:14:59.350 --> 00:15:00.833
which is the middle of the day.

00:15:01.970 --> 00:15:05.490
This is again, trying to achieve
kind of perfect schedule.

00:15:05.490 --> 00:15:09.140
Then I've recommended, based
on scientific literature,

00:15:09.140 --> 00:15:12.750
that you look at sunlight sometime around

00:15:12.750 --> 00:15:13.970
the time when the sun is setting

00:15:13.970 --> 00:15:15.320
and the reason for that of course

00:15:15.320 --> 00:15:19.230
is because it adjusts down
the sensitivity of your eyes

00:15:19.230 --> 00:15:21.740
because here's the diabolical thing.

00:15:21.740 --> 00:15:24.900
While we need a lot of photon
energy early in the day

00:15:24.900 --> 00:15:27.070
to wake up our system and
set our circadian clock,

00:15:27.070 --> 00:15:28.590
and prepare us for a good night's sleep

00:15:28.590 --> 00:15:30.700
14 to 16 hours later,

00:15:30.700 --> 00:15:33.040
it takes very little photon energy

00:15:33.040 --> 00:15:37.110
to reset and shift our
clock after 8:00 PM.

00:15:37.110 --> 00:15:39.960
And that's why you want to,
as much as you safely can,

00:15:39.960 --> 00:15:44.550
avoid bright light and
even not so bright light

00:15:44.550 --> 00:15:47.363
between the hours of 10
or 11:00 PM and 4:00 AM.

00:15:48.420 --> 00:15:51.150
