can shorten our lives,

00:23:49.120 --> 00:23:52.100
we have to ask ourselves why, why is that?

00:23:52.100 --> 00:23:53.680
And it turns out there's a pretty simple

00:23:53.680 --> 00:23:55.830
explanation for this.

00:23:55.830 --> 00:23:58.020
We've talked before about
the autonomic nervous system,

00:23:58.020 --> 00:24:01.240
this set of neurons in our
spinal cord and body and brain

00:24:01.240 --> 00:24:03.690
that regulate our wakefulness
and our sleepiness.

00:24:04.700 --> 00:24:08.470
Turns out that human beings,
and probably most species,

00:24:08.470 --> 00:24:12.110
are better able to activate and stay alert

00:24:12.110 --> 00:24:15.120
than they are to shut
down their nervous system

00:24:15.120 --> 00:24:16.500
and go to sleep on demand.

00:24:16.500 --> 00:24:18.620
So if you really have to push,

00:24:18.620 --> 00:24:20.340
and you really have to
stay awake, you can do it,

00:24:20.340 --> 00:24:22.050
you can stay up later.

00:24:22.050 --> 00:24:24.760
But falling asleep earlier is harder.

00:24:24.760 --> 00:24:26.340
And that's why traveling east

00:24:26.340 --> 00:24:29.550
has a number of different
features associated with it,

00:24:29.550 --> 00:24:31.690
that because you're traveling east

00:24:31.690 --> 00:24:34.440
you're trying to go to
bed earlier, you know.

00:24:34.440 --> 00:24:37.360
As a Californian, if
I go to New York city,

00:24:37.360 --> 00:24:38.940
I've got to get to bed three hours early

00:24:38.940 --> 00:24:40.160
and wake up three hours early,

00:24:40.160 --> 00:24:42.580
much harder than coming back to California

00:24:42.580 --> 00:24:44.490
and just staying up a few more hours.

00:24:44.490 --> 00:24:48.210
And this probably has roots in

00:24:48.210 --> 00:24:50.300
evolutionary adaptation where

00:24:50.300 --> 00:24:52.870
under conditions where we need
to suddenly gather up and go

00:24:52.870 --> 00:24:55.270
or forge for food, or fight,

00:24:55.270 --> 00:24:57.640
or do any number of different things,

00:24:57.640 --> 00:24:58.850
that we can push ourselves

00:24:58.850 --> 00:25:00.580
through the release of
adrenaline and epinephrin

00:25:00.580 --> 00:25:01.480
to stay awake.

00:25:01.480 --> 00:25:04.700
Whereas being able to slow down
and deliberately fall asleep

00:25:04.700 --> 00:25:06.690
is actually much harder to do.

00:25:06.690 --> 00:25:08.890
So there's an asymmetry to
our autonomic nervous system

00:25:08.890 --> 00:25:12.303
that plays out in the
asymmetry of jet lag.

00:25:13.400 --> 00:25:15.410
So, if you want to read up on this,

00:25:15.410 --> 00:25:18.350
because people have asked me
about papers, you can look,

00:25:18.350 --> 00:25:20.970
there's a paper published
by Davidson and colleagues,

00:25:20.970 --> 00:25:23.480
2006, in Current Biology that talks about

00:25:23.480 --> 00:25:25.850
the differences in life span

00:25:25.850 --> 00:25:29.960
for frequent eastward versus westward,

00:25:29.960 --> 00:25:34.120
versus no travel and longevity and etc.

00:25:34.120 --> 00:25:37.500
A number of different
biological markers of longevity.

00:25:37.500 --> 00:25:38.880
So going east is harder

00:25:39.760 --> 00:25:41.740
because going to sleep earlier is harder,

00:25:41.740 --> 00:25:44.200
if you're trying to do that on demand.

00:25:44.200 --> 00:25:45.700
Many people have turned to melatonin

00:25:45.700 --> 00:25:48.150
as a way to try and induce sleepiness.

00:25:48.150 --> 00:25:50.190
I'm going to talk about
melatonin at the end.

00:25:50.190 --> 00:25:52.010
I've mentioned on previous podcasts,

00:25:52.010 --> 00:25:54.040
a number of you have
asked for the evidence

00:25:54.040 --> 00:25:57.930
that melatonin is potentially detrimental

00:25:57.930 --> 00:26:00.660
to some hormone systems,
melatonin is a hormone.

00:26:00.660 --> 00:26:02.560
And I'll discuss that at the end,

00:26:02.560 --> 00:26:04.140
in particular, the role of melatonin

00:26:04.140 --> 00:26:06.250
in suppressing a hormone pathway

00:26:06.250 --> 00:26:08.120
that involves luteinizing hormone

00:26:08.120 --> 00:26:11.680
testosterone in men and
estrogen in females.

00:26:11.680 --> 00:26:13.554
As well as a really
interesting peptide called

00:26:13.554 --> 00:26:15.720
kisspeptin, that's a cool name.

00:26:15.720 --> 00:26:19.070
All right, well, let's think
about travel and what happens.

00:26:19.070 --> 00:26:22.640
Let's say you're not
going eastward or westward

00:26:22.640 --> 00:26:24.740
but you're going north or south.

00:26:24.740 --> 00:26:26.230
So if you go from for instance,

00:26:26.230 --> 00:26:28.713
Washington DC to Santiago Chile,

00:26:29.680 --> 00:26:34.680
or you go from Tel Aviv, Israel,
to Cape town, South Africa,

00:26:35.010 --> 00:26:38.030
you're just north and south, right?

00:26:38.030 --> 00:26:40.400
And not either direction.

00:26:40.400 --> 00:26:42.830
You're not really moving
into a different time zone,

00:26:42.830 --> 00:26:43.820
you're not shifting.

00:26:43.820 --> 00:26:47.060
So you will experience travel fatigue.

00:26:47.060 --> 00:26:48.960
And turns out that jet
lag has two elements,

00:26:48.960 --> 00:26:52.980
travel fatigue and time zone jet lag.

00:26:52.980 --> 00:26:56.690
Time zone jet lag is simply

00:26:56.690 --> 00:27:01.190
the inability of local
sunlight and local darkness

00:27:01.190 --> 00:27:03.670
to match to your internal rhythm,

00:27:03.670 --> 00:27:05.520
this endogenous rhythm that you have.

00:27:06.390 --> 00:27:09.330
So before we get too complicated

00:27:09.330 --> 00:27:11.820
and too down in the weeds about this,

00:27:11.820 --> 00:27:14.130
I want to just throw out
a couple important things.

00:27:14.130 --> 00:27:15.810
First of all, I mentioned this earlier,

00:27:15.810 --> 00:27:18.010
but some people suffer from jet lag a lot,

00:27:18.010 --> 00:27:20.050
other people not so much.

00:27:20.050 --> 00:27:24.290
Most people experience worse
jet lag as they get older.

00:27:24.290 --> 00:27:26.930
There are reasons for that
because early in life,

00:27:26.930 --> 00:27:29.520
patterns of melatonin release

00:27:29.520 --> 00:27:33.440
are very stable and flat and
very high actually in children.

00:27:33.440 --> 00:27:36.000
It's one of the reasons why
they don't undergo puberty.

00:27:36.000 --> 00:27:37.680
Then it becomes cyclical during puberty,

00:27:37.680 --> 00:27:40.600
meaning it comes on once every 24 hours

00:27:40.600 --> 00:27:44.230
and turns off once every 24
hours, it cycles, cyclic.

00:27:44.230 --> 00:27:47.540
And then as we get older,
the cycles get more disrupted

00:27:47.540 --> 00:27:49.210
and we become more vulnerable

00:27:49.210 --> 00:27:53.650
to even small changes in
schedule, etc, meal times, right?

00:27:53.650 --> 00:27:57.483
So, jet lag gets worse as we age.

00:27:58.630 --> 00:28:01.480
In addition, there are other
things that happen with age

00:28:01.480 --> 00:28:04.810
that people start doing less exercise,

00:28:04.810 --> 00:28:07.310
their digestion can get worse, etc.

00:28:07.310 --> 00:28:09.010
So some of the effects of age

00:28:09.010 --> 00:28:11.800
might not be direct
effects of getting older

00:28:11.800 --> 00:28:14.320
but some of the things that are
correlated with being older.

00:28:14.320 --> 00:28:15.770
Like people who are willing

00:28:15.770 --> 00:28:17.370
to have a regular exercise regime

00:28:17.370 --> 00:28:20.490
can use that exercise regime
to shift their circadian clock.

00:28:20.490 --> 00:28:24.410
And I have a good friend,
his father is in his 80s.

00:28:24.410 --> 00:28:29.410
He's still pushing out 25,
30 push-ups each morning,

00:28:29.470 --> 00:28:31.640
he's on the Peloton or whatever it is,

00:28:31.640 --> 00:28:32.473
doing a lot of cycling.

00:28:32.473 --> 00:28:35.330
So some 80-year olds are
doing that, many are not,

00:28:35.330 --> 00:28:37.280
many 30 year olds are not.

00:28:37.280 --> 00:28:40.380
But if you have a
regular exercise program,

00:28:40.380 --> 00:28:42.800
that's going to make it easier

00:28:42.800 --> 00:28:45.940
to shift your circadian clock
for the sake of jet lag.

00:28:45.940 --> 00:28:47.820
And it's actually a knob you can turn

00:28:47.820 --> 00:28:51.260
and you can leverage
for shifting your clock.

00:28:51.260 --> 00:28:52.390
Before we go any further,

00:28:52.390 --> 00:28:57.390
I want to make changing your
internal rhythm really easy.

00:28:57.950 --> 00:28:59.030
Or at least as easy

00:28:59.030 --> 00:29:02.143
and as simple as one could
possibly make it, I believe.

00:29:03.000 --> 00:29:04.370
What I want to talk about

00:29:04.370 --> 00:29:07.030
is perhaps one of the most
important things to know

00:29:07.030 --> 00:29:08.560
about your body and brain,

00:29:08.560 --> 00:29:10.930
which is called your
temperature minimum, okay?

00:29:10.930 --> 00:29:12.900
Most of you know your approximate weight,

00:29:12.900 --> 00:29:15.180
some of you might even
know your blood pressure,

00:29:15.180 --> 00:29:18.570
some of you might even
know your body mass index,

00:29:18.570 --> 00:29:20.670
some of you might know other
things about your biology

00:29:20.670 --> 00:29:22.380
that have fancy names,

00:29:22.380 --> 00:29:24.963
but everyone should know
their temperature minimum.

00:29:26.150 --> 00:29:27.630
Your temperature minimum

00:29:27.630 --> 00:29:29.550
doesn't require a thermometer to measure,

00:29:29.550 --> 00:29:31.420
although you could measure it.

00:29:31.420 --> 00:29:35.940
Your temperature minimum is the
point in every 24 hour cycle

00:29:35.940 --> 00:29:37.540
when your temperature is lowest.

00:29:38.920 --> 00:29:42.000
Now, how do you measure
that without a thermometer?

00:29:42.000 --> 00:29:44.380
It tends to fall 90 minutes to two hours

00:29:44.380 --> 00:29:47.040
before your average waking time.

00:29:47.040 --> 00:29:48.930
So I want to repeat that,
your temperature minimum

00:29:48.930 --> 00:29:52.770
tends to fall 90 minutes
to two hours before

00:29:52.770 --> 00:29:54.063
your average waking time.

00:29:54.980 --> 00:29:56.350
So let's say you're not traveling

00:29:56.350 --> 00:29:59.980
and your typical wake up time is 5:30 AM.

00:29:59.980 --> 00:30:04.950
Your temperature minimum is
very likely 3:30 AM or 4:00 AM.

00:30:04.950 --> 00:30:07.760
If you want, if any of you want to,

00:30:07.760 --> 00:30:09.300
you can measure your temperature minimum.

00:30:09.300 --> 00:30:10.210
You can get a thermometer

00:30:10.210 --> 00:30:11.960
and you can measure your
temperature every couple hours

00:30:11.960 --> 00:30:14.750
for 24 hours, and you can
find your temperature minimum.

00:30:14.750 --> 00:30:16.110
What you're going to find is that

00:30:16.110 --> 00:30:18.260
you have a low point,
the temperature minimum,

00:30:18.260 --> 00:30:19.930
and then your temperature
will start to rise,

00:30:19.930 --> 00:30:22.700
you'll wake up about two hours later.

00:30:22.700 --> 00:30:24.530
Then your temperature
will continue to rise

00:30:24.530 --> 00:30:26.390
into the afternoon it will peak,

00:30:26.390 --> 00:30:28.830
maybe a little trough,
sometimes that happens,

00:30:28.830 --> 00:30:33.220
and then it'll start declining slowly

00:30:33.220 --> 00:30:34.520
as you approach nighttime.

00:30:35.620 --> 00:30:38.320
There are things that will
disrupt that temperature pattern.

00:30:38.320 --> 00:30:42.890
Saunas, cold baths, intense exercise, etc.

00:30:42.890 --> 00:30:44.820
Meals tend to have a thermogenic effect

00:30:44.820 --> 00:30:47.030
that increases temperature
slightly little blips,

00:30:47.030 --> 00:30:50.340
but the overall cycle 24
hour cycle of temperature

00:30:50.340 --> 00:30:52.060
has this pattern.

00:30:52.060 --> 00:30:54.320
And last time I talked
about the seminal work

00:30:54.320 --> 00:30:57.660
of Joe Takahashi and others,
who have shown that temperature

00:30:57.660 --> 00:30:59.740
actually is the signal by which

00:30:59.740 --> 00:31:01.890
this clock above the roof of your mouth

00:31:01.890 --> 00:31:04.360
in-trains or collectively

00:31:04.360 --> 00:31:06.840
pushes all the cells
and tissues of our body

00:31:06.840 --> 00:31:08.750
to be on the same schedule.

00:31:08.750 --> 00:31:10.590
Temperature is the effector.

00:31:10.590 --> 00:31:13.630
And once you hear that there
should be an immediate,

00:31:13.630 --> 00:31:15.880
oh, of course, because
how else would you get

00:31:16.950 --> 00:31:19.270
all these different diverse cell types

00:31:19.270 --> 00:31:21.030
to follow one pattern, right?

00:31:21.030 --> 00:31:23.230
A pancreatic cell does
something very different

00:31:23.230 --> 00:31:27.970
than a spleen cell or a neuron, right?

00:31:27.970 --> 00:31:30.350
They're all doing different
things at different rates.

00:31:30.350 --> 00:31:31.880
So the temperature signal can go out

00:31:31.880 --> 00:31:32.720
and then each one of those

00:31:32.720 --> 00:31:34.100
can interpret the temperature signal

00:31:34.100 --> 00:31:38.840
as one unified and consistent
theme of their environment.

00:31:38.840 --> 00:31:42.400
So temperatures vary
from person to person.

00:31:42.400 --> 00:31:45.510
Some people are 98.6, some
people run a little colder, etc.

00:31:45.510 --> 00:31:47.810
But you have a low point,
and you have a high point.

00:31:47.810 --> 00:31:49.160
Know your temperature minimum.

00:31:49.160 --> 00:31:51.780
How are you going to figure
out this temperature minimum?

00:31:51.780 --> 00:31:54.320
The temperature minimum can be determined

00:31:54.320 --> 00:31:58.660
by taking the last three
to five wake up times.

00:31:58.660 --> 00:32:01.410
So let's say you wake up 7:00 AM,

00:32:01.410 --> 00:32:04.713
8:00 AM, 3:00 AM, all right it happens.

00:32:05.690 --> 00:32:08.450
Take those, add them
together, average them

00:32:08.450 --> 00:32:11.050
by adding them up and dividing
by the number of days,

00:32:11.050 --> 00:32:13.040
that'll give you the average.

00:32:13.040 --> 00:32:15.020
If you're one of these people
that wakes up at 3:00 AM

00:32:15.020 --> 00:32:16.940
and then goes back to
sleep and sleep till 10,

00:32:16.940 --> 00:32:19.230
your wake up time was 10:00 AM.

00:32:19.230 --> 00:32:20.720
If you use an alarm clock,

00:32:20.720 --> 00:32:24.203
your wake-up time is still
when you get up, okay?

00:32:25.520 --> 00:32:27.970
I know alarm clocks have
been kind of demonized

00:32:27.970 --> 00:32:29.340
but in my world

00:32:29.340 --> 00:32:31.770
being late and missing
appointments is also demonized,

00:32:31.770 --> 00:32:33.743
so I use an alarm clock.

00:32:35.780 --> 00:32:38.600
Many people will wake up at
exactly the same time each day,

00:32:38.600 --> 00:32:40.130
there tends to some variation for people.

00:32:40.130 --> 00:32:42.840
Some people it's going to vary
depending on life circumstances.

00:32:42.840 --> 00:32:45.363
But average that for
three to seven days or so.

00:32:46.320 --> 00:32:49.370
Take that wake up time,
you can then get an average

00:32:50.310 --> 00:32:52.620
or sort of typical temperature minimum.

00:32:52.620 --> 00:32:55.790
Okay, so now you know how to
get your temperature minimum.

00:32:55.790 --> 00:33:00.790
Your temperature minimum is
your absolute reference point

00:33:01.020 --> 00:33:03.750
for shifting your circadian clock.

00:33:03.750 --> 00:33:05.430
Whether or not it's for
jet lag, or shift work,

00:33:05.430 --> 00:33:07.030
or some other purpose.

00:33:07.030 --> 00:33:07.993
Here's the deal.

00:33:10.060 --> 00:33:12.970
If you expose your eyes to bright light

00:33:14.140 --> 00:33:17.350
in the four hours, maybe five or six,

00:33:17.350 --> 00:33:20.313
but in the four hours after
your temperature minimum,

00:33:21.610 --> 00:33:23.430
your circadian clock

00:33:24.720 --> 00:33:27.920
will shift so that you
will tend to get up earlier

00:33:27.920 --> 00:33:31.930
and go to sleep earlier in
the subsequent days, okay?

00:33:31.930 --> 00:33:34.010
So it's called a phase advance,

00:33:34.010 --> 00:33:35.940
if you'd like to read up on this further.

00:33:35.940 --> 00:33:39.040
You advance your clock, okay?

00:33:39.040 --> 00:33:42.660
However, if you view bright light

00:33:42.660 --> 00:33:45.973
in the four to six hours before
your temperature minimum,

00:33:47.650 --> 00:33:50.050
you will tend to phase delay your clock.

00:33:50.050 --> 00:33:54.400
You will tend to wake up
later and go to sleep later.

00:33:54.400 --> 00:33:55.320
Okay, I'm going to repeat this

00:33:55.320 --> 00:33:56.910
because there's so much
confusion out there

00:33:56.910 --> 00:33:58.880
and people talk about
circadian time and all this.

00:33:58.880 --> 00:34:00.240
Find your temperature minimum.

00:34:00.240 --> 00:34:02.910
I tend to wake up at about 6:00 AM,

00:34:02.910 --> 00:34:04.670
sometimes 6:30, sometimes seven.

00:34:04.670 --> 00:34:06.780
It depends a lot on what I
was doing the night before

00:34:06.780 --> 00:34:08.250
as I'm guessing it does for you.

00:34:08.250 --> 00:34:11.220
But that means that my temperature minimum

00:34:11.220 --> 00:34:14.220
is probably somewhere
right around 4:30 AM.

00:34:14.220 --> 00:34:17.700
Which means that if I wake up at 4:30 AM

00:34:17.700 --> 00:34:21.953
and I were to view
bright light at 4:35 AM,

00:34:22.870 --> 00:34:24.440
I'm going to advance my clock.

00:34:24.440 --> 00:34:28.150
I'm going to want to go to bed
earlier the subsequent night

00:34:28.150 --> 00:34:30.300
and wake up earlier
the subsequent morning.

00:34:31.250 --> 00:34:34.950
And as I shift my wake-up time,

00:34:34.950 --> 00:34:37.040
my temperature minimum shifts too, right?

00:34:37.040 --> 00:34:39.260
Because each time we
shift our wake-up time

00:34:39.260 --> 00:34:40.960
our temperature minimum shifts,

00:34:40.960 --> 00:34:42.400
assuming that wake up time

00:34:42.400 --> 00:34:45.913
shifts more than 30
minutes or an hour, okay.

00:34:47.240 --> 00:34:48.920
If I were to view bright light

00:34:48.920 --> 00:34:53.110
in the four to six hours
before 4:30 AM, guess what?

00:34:53.110 --> 00:34:55.460
The next night I'm going
to want to stay up later

00:34:55.460 --> 00:34:58.543
and I'm going to want to wake
up later the subsequent morning.

00:34:59.650 --> 00:35:01.840
Your temperature minimum
is a reference point

00:35:01.840 --> 00:35:03.980
not a temperature reading.

00:35:03.980 --> 00:35:06.560
Again, if you want to measure
your temperature minimum

00:35:06.560 --> 00:35:07.640
and figure out what it is,

00:35:07.640 --> 00:35:10.720
98 point whatever or 96
point whatever, that's fine.

00:35:10.720 --> 00:35:11.553
You can do that.

00:35:11.553 --> 00:35:12.630
But that information won't help you.

00:35:12.630 --> 00:35:14.990
What you need to know is what time

00:35:14.990 --> 00:35:16.280
your body temperature is lowest

00:35:16.280 --> 00:35:18.920
and understand that in
the four hours or so

00:35:18.920 --> 00:35:20.320
just after that time,

00:35:20.320 --> 00:35:22.810
viewing light will advance your clock

00:35:22.810 --> 00:35:24.510
to make you want to get up earlier.

00:35:26.410 --> 00:35:29.100
And the four hours before
your temperature minimum,

00:35:29.100 --> 00:35:33.520
viewing light will make
you want to stay up later.

00:35:33.520 --> 00:35:34.620
Now, some people might be saying,

00:35:34.620 --> 00:35:36.870
well, I wake up early and
I want to stay up late

00:35:36.870 --> 00:35:39.610
and I'm sleepy all day and
I'm a mess or I feel fine.

00:35:39.610 --> 00:35:42.970
Look, let's talk about feeling fine.

00:35:42.970 --> 00:35:45.860
Turns out the definition of insomnia

00:35:45.860 --> 00:35:47.640
is when you're experiencing

00:35:47.640 --> 00:35:49.880
excessive sleepiness during the day.

00:35:49.880 --> 00:35:52.730
Sleepiness and fatigue
are different, okay?

00:35:52.730 --> 00:35:54.470
So in the world of sleep medicine

00:35:54.470 --> 00:35:57.090
fatigue is a physical exhaustion,

00:35:57.090 --> 00:35:59.690
sleepiness is falling asleep.

00:35:59.690 --> 00:36:01.670
Like falling asleep at your desk

00:36:01.670 --> 00:36:03.050
or falling asleep during lectures,

00:36:03.050 --> 00:36:05.500
or there seems to be something
special about my lectures

00:36:05.500 --> 00:36:06.610
that makes people want to fall asleep.

00:36:06.610 --> 00:36:09.480
So if this cures your insomnia fantastic,

00:36:09.480 --> 00:36:11.203
however, in all seriousness,

00:36:12.620 --> 00:36:15.180
sleepiness during the day time

00:36:15.180 --> 00:36:17.320
unless it's around your temperature peak

00:36:17.320 --> 00:36:19.890
and only lasts about 90 minutes or so,

00:36:19.890 --> 00:36:22.140
is a sign of insomnia.

00:36:22.140 --> 00:36:23.663
It's a sign of lack of sleep.

00:36:26.670 --> 00:36:29.710
I want to be very, very clear that

00:36:29.710 --> 00:36:31.640
if you know your temperature minimum,

00:36:31.640 --> 00:36:34.160
you can shift your clock using light.

00:36:34.160 --> 00:36:38.390
You can also shift your
clock by engaging in exercise

00:36:38.390 --> 00:36:40.360
in the four hours after
your temperature minimum

00:36:40.360 --> 00:36:43.160
to wake up earlier on subsequent nights,

00:36:43.160 --> 00:36:46.440
or exercise before then
to delay your clock, okay?

00:36:46.440 --> 00:36:48.900
So now you can start to see and understand

00:36:48.900 --> 00:36:51.400
the logic of the system.

00:36:51.400 --> 00:36:53.080
And we'll talk about why this works

00:36:53.080 --> 00:36:54.290
and the underlying biology,

00:36:54.290 --> 00:36:58.180
but understanding that
temperature is the effector

00:36:58.180 --> 00:37:00.790
and understanding that
you have this low point

00:37:00.790 --> 00:37:03.160
that reflects your most sleepy point,

00:37:03.160 --> 00:37:05.420
essentially right before waking up,

00:37:05.420 --> 00:37:07.570
and then temperature rises,

00:37:07.570 --> 00:37:09.510
you can now start to
shift that temperature

00:37:09.510 --> 00:37:12.290
according to your travel needs.

00:37:12.290 --> 00:37:14.730
Here's one way in which you might do that.

00:37:14.730 --> 00:37:16.840
Let's say I am going to travel to Europe,

00:37:16.840 --> 00:37:20.973
which is nine hours ahead
typically, from California.

00:37:22.420 --> 00:37:24.530
I would want to determine
my temperature minimum

00:37:24.530 --> 00:37:27.630
which for me is about
4:30 AM maybe 5:00 AM,

00:37:27.630 --> 00:37:30.980
and I would want to start getting up

00:37:30.980 --> 00:37:35.980
at about 5:30 AM and getting
some bright light exposure,

00:37:36.140 --> 00:37:37.640
presumably from artificial sources

00:37:37.640 --> 00:37:41.260
because the sunlight isn't
going to be out at that time.

00:37:41.260 --> 00:37:42.680
Maybe even exercising as well,

00:37:42.680 --> 00:37:45.240
maybe even eating a meal at that time

00:37:45.240 --> 00:37:47.083
if that's in your practice.

00:37:48.290 --> 00:37:49.770
You would want to start doing that

00:37:49.770 --> 00:37:51.503
two or three days before travel.

00:37:53.280 --> 00:37:58.053
Because, once you land
in or I land in Europe,

00:37:59.160 --> 00:38:02.680
chances are just viewing the
sunrise or sunset in Europe

00:38:02.680 --> 00:38:05.460
is not going to allow me to
shift my circadian clock.

00:38:05.460 --> 00:38:07.610
Some people say get sunlight
in your eyes when you land

00:38:07.610 --> 00:38:09.790
but that's not going to work

00:38:09.790 --> 00:38:13.070
because one of two things
is likely to happen.

00:38:13.070 --> 00:38:14.470
With a nine hour shift like that

00:38:14.470 --> 00:38:16.390
either I'm going to view sunlight

00:38:16.390 --> 00:38:19.100
at a time that corresponds
to the circadian dead zone,

00:38:19.100 --> 00:38:22.530
the time in which my circadian
clock can't be shifted,

00:38:22.530 --> 00:38:24.980
or I'm going to end up viewing sunlight

00:38:24.980 --> 00:38:28.690
at a time that corresponds to
the four to six hour window

00:38:29.890 --> 00:38:32.700
before my temperature minimum.

00:38:32.700 --> 00:38:35.800
So it's going to shift me in
exactly the opposite direction

00:38:35.800 --> 00:38:37.210
that I want to go.

00:38:37.210 --> 00:38:39.870
So it can be very, very challenging

00:38:39.870 --> 00:38:41.980
for people to adjust to jet lag.

00:38:41.980 --> 00:38:44.280
So you need to ask, am I traveling east

00:38:44.280 --> 00:38:45.140
or am I traveling west?

00:38:45.140 --> 00:38:47.990
Am I trying to advance my
clock or delay my clock?

00:38:47.990 --> 00:38:51.820
Remember viewing light,
exercise and eating

00:38:51.820 --> 00:38:54.130
in the four to six hours
before your temperature minimum

00:38:54.130 --> 00:38:55.150
will delay your clock.

00:38:55.150 --> 00:38:58.290
Eating, viewing sunlight, and exercising,

00:38:58.290 --> 00:38:59.320
you don't have to do all three

00:38:59.320 --> 00:39:01.080
but some combination of those

00:39:01.080 --> 00:39:03.700
in the four to six hours
after your temperature minimum

00:39:03.700 --> 00:39:05.090
will advance your clock.

00:39:05.090 --> 00:39:06.710
And this is a powerful mechanism

00:39:06.710 --> 00:39:08.710
by which you can shift your clock anywhere

00:39:08.710 --> 00:39:13.180
from one to three hours per
day, which is remarkable.

00:39:13.180 --> 00:39:15.250
That means your temperature
minimum is going to shift out

00:39:15.250 --> 00:39:19.510
as much as three hours, which
can make it such that you can

00:39:19.510 --> 00:39:21.840
travel all the way to Europe

00:39:21.840 --> 00:39:24.970
and in as long as you've
prepared for a day or so

00:39:24.970 --> 00:39:27.850
by doing what I described back home

00:39:27.850 --> 00:39:30.210
and then doing it when you arrive,

00:39:30.210 --> 00:39:33.020
you can potentially accomplish
the entire shift within

00:39:33.020 --> 00:39:35.363
anywhere from 24 to 36 hours.

00:39:36.230 --> 00:39:40.120
And this is really important to emphasize

00:39:40.120 --> 00:39:42.640
that once you arrive in your new location

00:39:42.640 --> 00:39:44.070
and here I'm talking
about traveling eastward,

00:39:44.070 --> 00:39:47.393
California to Europe, once you
arrive in your new location,

00:39:48.750 --> 00:39:50.070
you have to keep track

00:39:50.070 --> 00:39:52.310
of what your temperature
minimum was back home

00:39:52.310 --> 00:39:54.510
and how it's being
shifted during your trip.

00:39:54.510 --> 00:39:56.730
Now it's much easier to do than you think.

00:39:56.730 --> 00:39:59.000
One of the unfortunate consequences

00:39:59.000 --> 00:40:02.040
of the smartphone is that

00:40:02.040 --> 00:40:05.450
you can't do something goofy
like wearing two watches.

00:40:05.450 --> 00:40:07.460
One watch that corresponds
to the time back home

00:40:07.460 --> 00:40:10.120
and another one that
corresponds to the local time.

00:40:10.120 --> 00:40:15.120
Typically it updates
automatically based on wifi, etc.

00:40:15.310 --> 00:40:19.320
But if you can keep track
of the time back home

00:40:19.320 --> 00:40:22.560
then you can easily shift
your clock going forward.

00:40:22.560 --> 00:40:24.170
I'm hoping this will makes sense.

00:40:24.170 --> 00:40:26.100
I really want to emphasize

00:40:26.100 --> 00:40:28.640
that you don't have to be
precise down to the minute.

00:40:28.640 --> 00:40:30.330
Some of you may be asking, well,

00:40:30.330 --> 00:40:32.410
what about you've got
this temperature minimum

00:40:32.410 --> 00:40:34.500
and if I view light one minute before it

00:40:34.500 --> 00:40:36.660
then I'm going to delay my
clock and one minute after it

00:40:36.660 --> 00:40:37.640
I'm going to advance my clock.

00:40:37.640 --> 00:40:40.220
It doesn't quite work like that, okay.

00:40:40.220 --> 00:40:42.790
But it's very important to understand

00:40:42.790 --> 00:40:44.160
that light is the primary way

00:40:44.160 --> 00:40:46.390
in which we can shift our clock.

00:40:46.390 --> 00:40:49.150
And now you should also
be able to understand

00:40:49.150 --> 00:40:51.560
things like the circadian
dead zone from about

00:40:51.560 --> 00:40:56.150
9:30, 10:00 AM all the way until

00:40:56.150 --> 00:40:58.810
six hours before your temperature minimum.

00:40:58.810 --> 00:41:00.290
You're not going to shift your clock.

00:41:00.290 --> 00:41:01.570
Nothing that you do in that time

00:41:01.570 --> 00:41:04.770
in terms of light viewing
behavior, feeding, etc,

00:41:04.770 --> 00:41:06.200
is going to shift your clock.

00:41:06.200 --> 00:41:08.320
And so a lot of people
are landing in Europe

00:41:08.320 --> 00:41:10.270
getting sunlight in their eyes

00:41:10.270 --> 00:41:12.860
and throwing their clock out of whack

00:41:12.860 --> 00:41:15.150
or not shifting their clock at all.

00:41:15.150 --> 00:41:18.410
This brings me to the other
thing that's highly recommended.

00:41:18.410 --> 00:41:19.440
And I've mentioned this before,

00:41:19.440 --> 00:41:21.810
but you want to eat on
the local meal schedule.

00:41:21.810 --> 00:41:26.260
If it's in your practice
to fast, fast, that's fine.

00:41:26.260 --> 00:41:28.300
But when you eat, you want to eat

00:41:28.300 --> 00:41:31.600
within the local schedule for alertness.

00:41:31.600 --> 00:41:32.433
Okay.

00:41:33.700 --> 00:41:35.960
That means if you arrive and
everyone's eating breakfast

00:41:35.960 --> 00:41:38.290
and you can't stomach
the idea of breakfast

00:41:38.290 --> 00:41:40.150
in your new location 'cause
your appetite isn't there.

00:41:40.150 --> 00:41:41.670
That means the clock in your liver,

00:41:41.670 --> 00:41:44.520
you have a clock in your
liver, biological clock,

00:41:44.520 --> 00:41:46.743
has not caught up to the new time zone.

00:41:48.230 --> 00:41:51.260
You can force yourself to eat if you like,

00:41:51.260 --> 00:41:53.240
or you can skip that meal.

00:41:53.240 --> 00:41:54.780
But what you don't want to do

00:41:54.780 --> 00:41:57.490
is stay on your home meal schedule,

00:41:57.490 --> 00:41:58.880
waking up in the middle
of the night and eating.

00:41:58.880 --> 00:42:00.450
That is really going to throw things off

00:42:00.450 --> 00:42:02.640
because a lot of the
clocks in the periphery

00:42:02.640 --> 00:42:04.680
like from the liver, the peripheral body,

00:42:04.680 --> 00:42:06.160
will send information back to the brain

00:42:06.160 --> 00:42:09.420
and then the brain is getting
really conflicted signals.

00:42:09.420 --> 00:42:12.300
So the temperature minimum
is really your anchor point

00:42:12.300 --> 00:42:14.220
for shifting your clock best.

00:42:14.220 --> 00:42:16.100
I don't know why this
information really hasn't made it

00:42:16.100 --> 00:42:19.190
into the popular sphere, quite so much.

00:42:19.190 --> 00:42:20.600
There's all sorts of stuff about

00:42:20.600 --> 00:42:23.830
taking things like melatonin,
using binaural beats,

00:42:23.830 --> 00:42:28.280
a lot of kind of like more
sophisticated, complicated,

00:42:28.280 --> 00:42:30.850
and potentially problematic

00:42:30.850 --> 00:42:32.670
ways of trying to shift the clock.

00:42:32.670 --> 00:42:35.920
Let's talk about melatonin
but first I just want to pause

00:42:35.920 --> 00:42:38.960
and shift gears a little bit

00:42:38.960 --> 00:42:41.640
because I talked about traveling eastward,

00:42:41.640 --> 00:42:44.020
but we haven't talked
about traveling westward.

00:42:44.020 --> 00:42:45.420
So I want to do that now.

00:42:45.420 --> 00:42:47.700
Let's say you're raveling
from New York to California

00:42:47.700 --> 00:42:49.840
or from Europe to California.

00:42:49.840 --> 00:42:52.270
The challenge there tends to be,

00:42:52.270 --> 00:42:54.260
how can you stay up late enough?

00:42:54.260 --> 00:42:56.310
Now, some people are able to do this

00:42:56.310 --> 00:42:57.720
because as I mentioned earlier,

00:42:57.720 --> 00:43:00.840
the autonomic nervous system
is asymmetrically wired

00:43:00.840 --> 00:43:03.060
such that it's easier to stay up late

00:43:03.060 --> 00:43:05.250
later than we would naturally want to

00:43:05.250 --> 00:43:06.730
than it is to go to sleep earlier.

00:43:06.730 --> 00:43:09.860
So let's say you land and it's 4:00 PM

00:43:09.860 --> 00:43:12.360
and you're just dying,
you're in California,

00:43:12.360 --> 00:43:13.670
you came from Europe, it's 4:00 PM

00:43:13.670 --> 00:43:16.570
and you really, really
want to go to sleep.

00:43:16.570 --> 00:43:19.980
That's where the use of things
like caffeine, exercise,

00:43:19.980 --> 00:43:22.450
and sunlight can shift you, right?

00:43:22.450 --> 00:43:24.770
If it's after your temperature peak

00:43:24.770 --> 00:43:27.700
then viewing sunlight
around 6:00 PM or 8:00 PM

00:43:27.700 --> 00:43:31.200
or artificial light, if
there isn't sunlight,

00:43:31.200 --> 00:43:33.540
will help shift you later, right?

00:43:33.540 --> 00:43:35.222
It's going to delay your clock

00:43:35.222 --> 00:43:37.293
and you're going to be
able to stay up later.

00:43:38.450 --> 00:43:40.180
The worst thing you can do is take a nap

00:43:40.180 --> 00:43:43.150
that was intended to last
20 minutes or an hour.

00:43:43.150 --> 00:43:46.130
I do this routinely and then
wake up four hours later

00:43:46.130 --> 00:43:48.320
or you wake up and it's midnight

00:43:48.320 --> 00:43:49.500
and you can't fall back asleep.

00:43:49.500 --> 00:43:52.090
You really want to avoid doing that.

00:43:52.090 --> 00:43:55.130
So provided it's not excessive amounts,

00:43:55.130 --> 00:43:57.760
stimulants like caffeine and coffee or tea

00:43:57.760 --> 00:44:00.960
can really help you push
past that afternoon barrier

00:44:00.960 --> 00:44:05.070
and get you to sleep more
like on the local schedule.

00:44:05.070 --> 00:44:07.963
And eating on the local schedule as well.

00:44:09.520 --> 00:44:11.130
A number of people have asked about

00:44:11.130 --> 00:44:13.930
the use of melatonin to induce sleepiness.

00:44:13.930 --> 00:44:16.780
All right, well let's think
about what melatonin is.

00:44:16.780 --> 00:44:18.020
Melatonin is this hormone

00:44:18.020 --> 00:44:21.310
that's released from the pineal
gland, which is this gland.

00:44:21.310 --> 00:44:23.090
A couple of notes about the pineal,

00:44:23.090 --> 00:44:25.160
'cause I've been getting a
lot of questions about this.

00:44:25.160 --> 00:44:26.690
I'm probably going to
draw some fire for this

00:44:26.690 --> 00:44:31.690
but I'd be happy to have a
thoughtful, considerate debate,

00:44:31.700 --> 00:44:34.820
with some peer reviewed
papers in front of us.

00:44:34.820 --> 00:44:37.910
The pineal does make this
hallucinogenic molecule

00:44:37.910 --> 00:44:39.710
they call DMT,

00:44:39.710 --> 00:44:42.720
but in such a minuscule amounts
that it is not responsible

00:44:42.720 --> 00:44:45.240
for the hallucinations you
see in sleep and dreaming.

00:44:45.240 --> 00:44:46.140
Sorry, folks.

00:44:46.140 --> 00:44:47.170
It's also not responsible

00:44:47.170 --> 00:44:48.880
for the hallucinations you might see

00:44:48.880 --> 00:44:51.140
through other approaches to DMT.

00:44:51.140 --> 00:44:53.710
It's just not, that's not
where the DMT comes from.

00:44:53.710 --> 00:44:56.463
It's infinitesimally small amounts.

00:44:57.760 --> 00:44:59.970
There are a lot of kind
of wacky claims out there

00:44:59.970 --> 00:45:03.430
about calcification of
the pineal and fluoride

00:45:03.430 --> 00:45:04.580
and this kind of thing.

00:45:05.680 --> 00:45:10.680
Look, the pineal sits
in an area of the brain

00:45:10.720 --> 00:45:12.290
near the fourth ventricle,

00:45:12.290 --> 00:45:16.320
where the skull is not terribly far away

00:45:16.320 --> 00:45:18.660
although there's some
overlap in neural tissue

00:45:18.660 --> 00:45:22.210
and with age there's some aggregation

00:45:22.210 --> 00:45:25.020
of some of the meninges and
other things around there

00:45:25.020 --> 00:45:26.320
that stick to the skull.

00:45:26.320 --> 00:45:27.900
Young brains don't look like old brains

00:45:27.900 --> 00:45:30.930
but there's no calcification
of the pineal, all right?

00:45:30.930 --> 00:45:33.550
So you can forget about
calcification of the pineal

00:45:33.550 --> 00:45:35.210
as a problem.

00:45:35.210 --> 00:45:36.970
I don't know where that
whole thing got started

00:45:36.970 --> 00:45:39.020
but that's not an issue.

00:45:39.020 --> 00:45:43.260
Your pineal will churn out
melatonin your whole life.

00:45:43.260 --> 00:45:45.700
Melatonin induces sleepiness.

00:45:45.700 --> 00:45:49.670
Melatonin during development
is also responsible

00:45:49.670 --> 00:45:52.340
for timing the secretion
of certain hormones

00:45:52.340 --> 00:45:55.273
that are vitally important for puberty.

00:45:56.190 --> 00:45:58.940
Does melatonin control
the onset of puberty?

00:45:58.940 --> 00:46:01.540
Not directly, but indirectly.

00:46:01.540 --> 00:46:03.670
Melatonin inhibits something called

00:46:03.670 --> 00:46:05.210
gonadotropin-releasing hormone,

00:46:05.210 --> 00:46:07.380
which is a hormone that's
released from your hypothalamus

00:46:07.380 --> 00:46:10.150
also roughly above the roof
of your mouth in your brain.

00:46:10.150 --> 00:46:11.990
Gonadotropin-releasing
hormone is really interesting

00:46:11.990 --> 00:46:14.370
'cause it stimulates the
release of another hormone

00:46:14.370 --> 00:46:17.850
called luteinizing hormone,
which in females causes

00:46:18.990 --> 00:46:22.570
estrogen to be released
within the ovaries,

00:46:22.570 --> 00:46:24.290
it's involved in reproductive cycles,

00:46:24.290 --> 00:46:27.380
and in males stimulates testosterone

00:46:27.380 --> 00:46:30.443
from the sertoli cells of the testes.

00:46:31.700 --> 00:46:34.640
Melatonin is inhibitory to GnRH,

00:46:34.640 --> 00:46:35.930
gonadotropin-releasing hormone,

00:46:35.930 --> 00:46:38.640
and therefore is inhibitory
to LH, luteinizing hormone,

00:46:38.640 --> 00:46:41.610
and therefore is inhibitory
to testosterone and estrogen.

00:46:41.610 --> 00:46:43.310
There's just no two ways about it.

00:46:45.500 --> 00:46:50.500
There is immense amount
of data on the fact that

00:46:50.560 --> 00:46:54.400
high levels of melatonin in
seasonally breeding animals,

00:46:54.400 --> 00:46:57.040
takes the ovaries from
nice and robust ovaries

00:46:57.040 --> 00:47:00.170
that are capable of deploying
eggs and this kind of thing

00:47:00.170 --> 00:47:02.060
and literally shrinking them

00:47:02.060 --> 00:47:04.400
and making these animals infertile.

00:47:04.400 --> 00:47:05.810
These are very high levels of melatonin

00:47:05.810 --> 00:47:07.403
in seasonal breeders in winter.

00:47:08.250 --> 00:47:11.570
Melatonin in males of seasonal breeders

00:47:11.570 --> 00:47:13.930
takes the testes and shrinks them.

00:47:13.930 --> 00:47:17.760
Long ago when I was at UC,
Berkeley as a master's student,

00:47:17.760 --> 00:47:19.880
I was working on neuroendocrinology,

00:47:19.880 --> 00:47:21.630
and we were working on

00:47:21.630 --> 00:47:23.530
this hamster species of seasonal breeders.

00:47:23.530 --> 00:47:27.520
And basically when days are
long, which inhibits melatonin,

00:47:27.520 --> 00:47:30.870
these little Siberian
hamsters as they're called,

00:47:30.870 --> 00:47:34.780
have testes about the size of,
sort of typical table grapes,

00:47:34.780 --> 00:47:36.680
although that's a weird way to put it.

00:47:37.890 --> 00:47:41.040
When days get shorter and the
melatonin signal gets longer

00:47:41.040 --> 00:47:42.400
because light inhibits melatonin,

00:47:42.400 --> 00:47:43.970
days get shorter, melatonin gets longer.

00:47:43.970 --> 00:47:46.710
Those same hamsters would have testes

00:47:46.710 --> 00:47:49.480
that would involute to the
size of about a grain of rice.

00:47:49.480 --> 00:47:53.820
Now this does not happen
in humans in short days.

00:47:53.820 --> 00:47:57.230
But nonetheless, the melatonin
signal really does have

00:47:57.230 --> 00:47:59.130
a ton of effects on the hormone system.

00:47:59.130 --> 00:48:02.150
Now, does that mean that if
you've been taking melatonin

00:48:02.150 --> 00:48:03.260
you've really screwed up your hormones?

00:48:03.260 --> 00:48:04.093
Not necessarily.

00:48:04.093 --> 00:48:05.810
Does it mean if a kid
has been taking melatonin

00:48:05.810 --> 00:48:07.370
that's really screwing up their puberty?

00:48:07.370 --> 00:48:09.143
Not necessarily and here's why.

00:48:11.910 --> 00:48:15.620
Melatonin operates on
a concentration level.

00:48:15.620 --> 00:48:18.600
So in a child that's very, very small

00:48:19.530 --> 00:48:21.250
that has high levels of melatonin,

00:48:21.250 --> 00:48:24.388
it actually can inhibit GnRH, LH,

00:48:24.388 --> 00:48:28.000
testosterone or estrogen
depending on the sex of the child.

00:48:28.000 --> 00:48:30.350
But as that child grows
through other mechanisms,

00:48:30.350 --> 00:48:32.100
like growth hormone release, etc,

00:48:32.100 --> 00:48:34.450
that same amount of melatonin
released from the pineal

00:48:34.450 --> 00:48:36.730
is now diluted over a much larger body

00:48:36.730 --> 00:48:40.850
so that the concentration
actually goes way, way down, okay?

00:48:40.850 --> 00:48:43.240
But here's the problem with
supplementing melatonin.

00:48:43.240 --> 00:48:45.260
As I mentioned in the previous episode,

00:48:45.260 --> 00:48:48.320
concentrations of melatonin
in many commercial supplements

00:48:48.320 --> 00:48:52.460
have been shown to be
anywhere from 85% to 400%

00:48:52.460 --> 00:48:54.520
of what's listed on the bottle.

00:48:54.520 --> 00:48:57.330
So when you take melatonin
or a child takes melatonin

00:48:57.330 --> 00:49:00.500
oftentimes they are
taking super physiological

00:49:00.500 --> 00:49:01.870
levels of melatonin,

00:49:01.870 --> 00:49:06.540
which at least by my
read, and the literature,

00:49:06.540 --> 00:49:08.820
says that it could have dramatic effects

00:49:08.820 --> 00:49:12.680
on timing and course
of things like puberty.

00:49:12.680 --> 00:49:16.190
So it's not so much that the
journals have come out saying,

00:49:16.190 --> 00:49:19.550
oh, taking that melatonin
inhibits puberty,

00:49:19.550 --> 00:49:21.320
it's that no single study has been done

00:49:21.320 --> 00:49:23.820
with the super physiological
levels of melatonin

00:49:23.820 --> 00:49:26.150
that are present in a
lot of these supplements

00:49:26.150 --> 00:49:29.100
in developing children.

00:49:29.100 --> 00:49:33.760
So melatonin is used widely
for inducing sleepiness

00:49:33.760 --> 00:49:34.900
when you want to fall asleep

00:49:34.900 --> 00:49:37.390
in the new location that
you've arrived, right?

00:49:37.390 --> 00:49:38.940
You can't fall asleep, you take melatonin,

00:49:38.940 --> 00:49:40.530
it helps you fall asleep.

00:49:40.530 --> 00:49:42.950
It does not help you stay asleep.

00:49:42.950 --> 00:49:46.810
In addition to that, melatonin
has been kind of touted

00:49:46.810 --> 00:49:49.510
as the best way to shift
your circadian clock.

00:49:49.510 --> 00:49:51.300
I'm happy to go on record saying,

00:49:51.300 --> 00:49:53.440
look, if you need melatonin,
you can work with a doctor

00:49:53.440 --> 00:49:54.600
or somebody who really understands

00:49:54.600 --> 00:49:57.980
circadian and sleep biology go
for it, if that's your thing.

00:49:57.980 --> 00:50:01.730
But I, as always on this
podcast and elsewhere,

00:50:01.730 --> 00:50:05.710
I have a bias toward behavioral things

00:50:05.710 --> 00:50:07.010
that you can titrate and control

00:50:07.010 --> 00:50:09.910
like exposure to light
exercise, temperature, etc,

00:50:09.910 --> 00:50:12.710
that have much bigger margins for safety

00:50:12.710 --> 00:50:14.730
and certainly don't have
these other endocrine effects

00:50:14.730 --> 00:50:17.420
that we've been thinking
about and talking about.

00:50:17.420 --> 00:50:20.730
So if you want to take
melatonin in the afternoon

00:50:20.730 --> 00:50:22.840
in order to fall asleep or in the evening,

00:50:22.840 --> 00:50:24.890
be my guest, that's up to you.

00:50:24.890 --> 00:50:27.750
Again, you're responsible
for your health, not me.

00:50:27.750 --> 00:50:29.670
But for many people

00:50:29.670 --> 00:50:32.310
melatonin is not going
to be the best solution.

00:50:32.310 --> 00:50:34.760
The best solution is going to be to use

00:50:34.760 --> 00:50:36.960
light and temperature, and exercise

00:50:36.960 --> 00:50:39.220
on either side of the temperature minimum

00:50:39.220 --> 00:50:41.090
to shift your clock both before your trip

00:50:41.090 --> 00:50:42.810
and when you land in your new location

00:50:42.810 --> 00:50:44.690
and your clock starts to shift.

00:50:44.690 --> 00:50:47.840
Okay, so now you know my
opinions about melatonin,

00:50:47.840 --> 00:50:49.950
feel free to filter them through

00:50:49.950 --> 00:50:53.360
your own opinions and
experiences with melatonin.

00:50:53.360 --> 00:50:55.320
And now you also understand

00:50:55.320 --> 00:50:56.940
what your temperature minimum is

00:50:56.940 --> 00:50:59.610
and how it represents
an important landmark

00:50:59.610 --> 00:51:02.070
either side of which you can use

00:51:02.070 --> 00:51:05.530
light, temperature, and
exercise to shift your clock.

00:51:05.530 --> 00:51:07.140
Just to remind you a little
bit about temperature,

00:51:07.140 --> 00:51:09.890
if you want to shift your clock,

00:51:09.890 --> 00:51:13.160
typically you would do that
by you can take a hot shower

00:51:13.160 --> 00:51:15.230
and then that will have a cooling effect

00:51:15.230 --> 00:51:16.593
after the hot shower.

00:51:17.680 --> 00:51:20.140
And if you were to get into a cold shower

00:51:20.140 --> 00:51:22.270
or an ice bath if you have access to one,

00:51:22.270 --> 00:51:24.560
afterward there's going
to be a thermogenic effect

00:51:24.560 --> 00:51:26.750
of your body increasing temperature.

00:51:26.750 --> 00:51:30.090
And if you just think about
your natural rhythm back home

00:51:30.090 --> 00:51:31.343
when everything's stable,

00:51:32.400 --> 00:51:34.870
you have an idea a low point

00:51:34.870 --> 00:51:36.660
in which is your temperature minimum,

00:51:36.660 --> 00:51:38.010
and then you have a peak,

00:51:38.010 --> 00:51:39.810
and you think about when you're doing this

00:51:39.810 --> 00:51:42.610
hot or cold shower in that rhythm,

00:51:42.610 --> 00:51:44.040
now you should be able to understand

00:51:44.040 --> 00:51:45.740
how you're shifting your rhythm.

00:51:45.740 --> 00:51:48.090
That temperature rhythm is
the one that's going to move.

00:51:48.090 --> 00:51:49.480
Give you an example.

00:51:49.480 --> 00:51:51.780
If I were to wake up in the morning

00:51:51.780 --> 00:51:54.490
and let's say I wake up at 6:00 AM.

00:51:54.490 --> 00:51:55.990
My temperature I know is rising,

00:51:55.990 --> 00:51:57.660
I've passed my temperature minimum.

00:51:57.660 --> 00:52:00.283
If I were to get into a hot shower,

00:52:01.330 --> 00:52:04.460
that would then lower my body
temperature when I got out,

00:52:04.460 --> 00:52:06.440
that is not normally what's happening

00:52:06.440 --> 00:52:09.190
first thing in the morning, and therefore

00:52:09.190 --> 00:52:12.500
my clock would very likely
get phase delayed, right?

00:52:12.500 --> 00:52:15.180
It's going to delay the
increase in temperature.

00:52:15.180 --> 00:52:17.400
Whereas if I got into a cold shower,

00:52:17.400 --> 00:52:18.680
something I don't personally like to do,

00:52:18.680 --> 00:52:21.610
but I've done from time
to time or an ice bath

00:52:21.610 --> 00:52:22.480
that's going to then

00:52:22.480 --> 00:52:24.900
have a rebound increase
in body temperature

00:52:24.900 --> 00:52:26.730
and is going to phase advance my clock.

00:52:26.730 --> 00:52:28.920
That peak in the
afternoon is going to come

00:52:28.920 --> 00:52:30.400
about an hour earlier.

00:52:30.400 --> 00:52:33.030
I'm going to want to go to
bed earlier, later that night.

00:52:33.030 --> 00:52:34.340
So you can start to play these games

00:52:34.340 --> 00:52:36.450
with timing and hot and cold,

00:52:36.450 --> 00:52:38.970
with meals whether or not
you eat, or you don't eat,

00:52:38.970 --> 00:52:40.180
and with light exposure,

00:52:40.180 --> 00:52:42.660
whether or not you view light
or you don't view light.

00:52:42.660 --> 00:52:44.630
So now you can start to
see why understanding

00:52:44.630 --> 00:52:46.700
the core mechanics of a system

00:52:46.700 --> 00:52:49.100
can really give you the
most flexibility because

00:52:50.300 --> 00:52:53.230
I could spend the next 25 years of my life

00:52:53.230 --> 00:52:55.410
answering every question about every

00:52:55.410 --> 00:52:56.770
nuance pattern of travel.

00:52:56.770 --> 00:52:58.740
Well, we're going to Sydney
and then we're going there,

00:52:58.740 --> 00:52:59.650
what should I do?

00:52:59.650 --> 00:53:00.810
But that's on you.

00:53:00.810 --> 00:53:02.020
You need to figure out

00:53:02.020 --> 00:53:03.920
your temperature minimum
and your temperature peak,

00:53:03.920 --> 00:53:06.200
if you like, and then
use these parameters to

00:53:06.200 --> 00:53:07.460
it gives you flexibility.

00:53:07.460 --> 00:53:09.490
And that really underscores
the most important thing

00:53:09.490 --> 00:53:12.490
is that when you understand
mechanism it's not about

00:53:12.490 --> 00:53:14.700
being neurotically attached
to a specific protocol,

00:53:14.700 --> 00:53:15.830
it's the opposite.

00:53:15.830 --> 00:53:18.650
It gives you power to not
be neurotically attached

00:53:18.650 --> 00:53:20.030
to a specific protocol.

00:53:20.030 --> 00:53:22.700
It can give you great
confidence and flexibility

00:53:22.700 --> 00:53:24.770
in being able to shift your
body rhythms however you want.

00:53:24.770 --> 00:53:25.750
And when things get out of whack

00:53:25.750 --> 00:53:27.750
you can tuck them right back into place.

00:53:28.870 --> 00:53:30.710
One thing that's common

00:53:30.710 --> 00:53:32.680
is that people need to do a quick trip.

00:53:32.680 --> 00:53:34.460
It's not always that
you're going to go to,

00:53:34.460 --> 00:53:36.810
you know on vacation for two weeks or,

00:53:36.810 --> 00:53:40.113
you know, work someplace
else for weeks on end.

00:53:41.370 --> 00:53:44.690
If your trip is 48 hours or less,

00:53:44.690 --> 00:53:46.610
stay on your home schedule.

00:53:46.610 --> 00:53:50.130
This can be tough and it may
require scheduling meetings

00:53:50.130 --> 00:53:52.260
according to your home schedule,

00:53:52.260 --> 00:53:55.470
but if you can somehow manage that

00:53:55.470 --> 00:53:58.050
the best thing to do would be
to stay on your home schedule.

00:53:58.050 --> 00:54:01.500
Your clock is not going to
shift more than a couple hours,

00:54:01.500 --> 00:54:03.340
even if you do everything correctly

00:54:04.710 --> 00:54:06.100
in one day, okay?

00:54:06.100 --> 00:54:09.230
So if I were to travel, say to Europe,

00:54:09.230 --> 00:54:10.110
I've actually done this,

00:54:10.110 --> 00:54:12.310
I did a 24 hour trip
to Basel, Switzerland,

00:54:12.310 --> 00:54:15.590
gave a talk and came back,
people thought I was crazy but,

00:54:15.590 --> 00:54:16.870
I had a little bit of travel fatigue

00:54:16.870 --> 00:54:17.850
'cause remember there's fatigue

00:54:17.850 --> 00:54:19.840
from the actual travel experience.

00:54:19.840 --> 00:54:23.710
The novelty of it, the air
is never great on the planes,

00:54:23.710 --> 00:54:25.920
this was even true before
there were mask requirements

00:54:25.920 --> 00:54:27.130
and things like that.

00:54:27.130 --> 00:54:28.280
There's the travel fatigue

00:54:28.280 --> 00:54:30.720
but you don't throw your clock off.

00:54:30.720 --> 00:54:33.180
If you stay 48 hours,

00:54:33.180 --> 00:54:36.480
then you start to shift a little bit.

00:54:36.480 --> 00:54:38.890
72, that's when you start
running into trouble.

00:54:38.890 --> 00:54:41.210
The transit time is also important

00:54:41.210 --> 00:54:43.610
but I would say if it's
three days or less,

00:54:43.610 --> 00:54:46.850
stay on your home schedule
as much as you can.

00:54:46.850 --> 00:54:49.970
And because sunlight
isn't under your control

00:54:49.970 --> 00:54:52.000
unless there's something
about you I don't know,

00:54:52.000 --> 00:54:54.620
that's when traveling with
some sort of bright light

00:54:54.620 --> 00:54:56.550
like the light pad that I have

00:54:56.550 --> 00:54:58.750
down there that I showed earlier,

00:54:58.750 --> 00:55:00.120
for those of you listening just on audio,

00:55:00.120 --> 00:55:03.360
it sort of looks like an eight
and a half by 11 inch pad.

00:55:03.360 --> 00:55:04.870
It's actually not designed for wake up,

00:55:04.870 --> 00:55:07.020
it's actually designed,
it's a drawing pad,

00:55:07.942 --> 00:55:12.180
and it emits about 1,000 lux of light.

00:55:12.180 --> 00:55:15.120
And so if you want to travel
with something like that,

00:55:15.120 --> 00:55:16.850
you can use that in your hotel room

00:55:16.850 --> 00:55:19.300
to wake up when you like.

00:55:19.300 --> 00:55:22.230
Some people will use night shades,

00:55:22.230 --> 00:55:24.670
you know, not the night
shades that you eat

00:55:24.670 --> 00:55:26.129
or that some people say
you're not supposed to eat,

00:55:26.129 --> 00:55:27.110
I don't know anything about that,

00:55:27.110 --> 00:55:32.110
but the eye covers to keep light out.

00:55:32.120 --> 00:55:36.530
Those can be very useful on
planes and in hotels and so on.

00:55:36.530 --> 00:55:38.650
So you can use light and dark

00:55:38.650 --> 00:55:42.340
or you can travel with
your light and dark devices

00:55:42.340 --> 00:55:44.270
so that you can stay on your home schedule

00:55:44.270 --> 00:55:45.300
and get most of your light

00:55:45.300 --> 00:55:48.730
when it would be your normal
wake up time back home.

00:55:48.730 --> 00:55:50.783
And what's kind of nice is if you know

00:55:50.783 --> 00:55:53.380
when your circadian
dead zone is back home,

00:55:53.380 --> 00:55:55.880
which is generally for most people around

00:55:56.948 --> 00:55:59.660
10:00 AM to about 3:00 PM,

00:55:59.660 --> 00:56:02.950
so basically the rising
phase of your temperature,

00:56:02.950 --> 00:56:06.670
then you can also feel free to be outside

00:56:06.670 --> 00:56:08.020
without having to wear sunglasses

00:56:08.020 --> 00:56:09.910
or you don't have to worry
about light exposure.

00:56:09.910 --> 00:56:14.520
But if you know that window
before your temperature minimum,

00:56:14.520 --> 00:56:15.950
that four to six hour window,

00:56:15.950 --> 00:56:17.990
that's the time when if
you're viewing a lot of light

00:56:17.990 --> 00:56:19.510
in your new location,

00:56:19.510 --> 00:56:21.980
you are going to shift your
clock pretty considerably

00:56:21.980 --> 00:56:24.710
and then you can come back
home and have a terrible time.

00:56:24.710 --> 00:56:27.760
At the end of graduate
school, I went to Australia,

00:56:27.760 --> 00:56:30.880
remarkable country, incredible
people, incredible wildlife,

00:56:30.880 --> 00:56:32.400
had amazing time, I came back

00:56:32.400 --> 00:56:34.240
and it was the first time in my life

00:56:34.240 --> 00:56:36.540
where I couldn't sleep
on a regular schedule.

00:56:36.540 --> 00:56:37.580
I was sleeping in like

00:56:37.580 --> 00:56:40.910
hour long increments throughout
the day, it was a nightmare.

00:56:40.910 --> 00:56:44.490
And it took me weeks
to get back on target.

00:56:44.490 --> 00:56:46.170
And the way I was able to do that

00:56:46.170 --> 00:56:50.620
was exercising consistently at
the same time every 24 hours,

00:56:50.620 --> 00:56:54.810
turning my home into
essentially a cave at night,

00:56:54.810 --> 00:56:56.440
even covering up the windows

00:56:56.440 --> 00:56:58.530
and then getting as much
bright light in my eyes

00:56:58.530 --> 00:57:01.980
as I possibly could during
the day, no sunglasses, etc.

00:57:01.980 --> 00:57:03.230
So it can take some real work

00:57:03.230 --> 00:57:05.560
if your clock gets thrown out of whack.

00:57:05.560 --> 00:57:08.630
There's a phenomenon called ICU psychosis,

00:57:08.630 --> 00:57:10.080
where people that are in

00:57:10.080 --> 00:57:11.780
the intensive care unit in hospitals

00:57:11.780 --> 00:57:13.470
actually lose their mind.

00:57:13.470 --> 00:57:18.033
They become psychotic,
hallucinations, etc.

00:57:18.920 --> 00:57:21.280
And it's because of
altered circadian cycles.

00:57:21.280 --> 00:57:23.757
We know this 'cause they're
exposed to these lights

00:57:23.757 --> 00:57:26.050
and these sounds, people
coming in and checking on them.

00:57:26.050 --> 00:57:28.220
They leave the hospital or in some cases,

00:57:28.220 --> 00:57:29.520
there have been experiments
where people are placed

00:57:29.520 --> 00:57:31.580
near a window where they
get some natural light

00:57:31.580 --> 00:57:33.810
and the psychotic symptoms disappear,

00:57:33.810 --> 00:57:37.250
presuming there weren't
psychotic symptoms beforehand,

00:57:37.250 --> 00:57:38.810
before they entered the hospital.

00:57:38.810 --> 00:57:42.830
So it's pretty dramatic what light can do

00:57:42.830 --> 00:57:44.890
to the psyche and to the body.

00:57:44.890 --> 00:57:47.490
So let's talk a little bit

00:57:47.490 --> 00:57:49.180
about a different form of jet lag

00:57:49.180 --> 00:57:52.970
that requires no planes,
no trains, no automobiles,

00:57:52.970 --> 00:57:54.463
and that's shift work.

00:57:55.450 --> 00:57:58.223
Shift work is becoming
increasingly common.

00:57:59.320 --> 00:58:02.090
Many of us are shift working
even though we don't have to.

00:58:02.090 --> 00:58:03.950
We're doing work in the
middle of the night,

00:58:03.950 --> 00:58:08.240
we are, you know, working on
our computers at odd hours,

00:58:08.240 --> 00:58:09.290
sleeping during the day.

00:58:09.290 --> 00:58:13.520
A lot of people who are under
shelter and place type stuff,

00:58:13.520 --> 00:58:15.180
are doing more of this.

00:58:15.180 --> 00:58:18.090
Kids with the drifting school schedules.

00:58:18.090 --> 00:58:19.800
Here's the deal with shift work.

00:58:19.800 --> 00:58:22.700
If there's one rule of
thumb for shift work,

00:58:22.700 --> 00:58:25.053
it's that if at all possible,

00:58:25.900 --> 00:58:29.860
you want to stay on the same
schedule for at least 14 days,

00:58:29.860 --> 00:58:31.690
including weekends.

00:58:31.690 --> 00:58:34.950
Now that should immediately
cue the non shift workers

00:58:34.950 --> 00:58:37.670
to the importance of not
getting too far off track

00:58:37.670 --> 00:58:39.390
on the weekend, even if
you're not a shift worker.

00:58:39.390 --> 00:58:43.033
So sleeping in on Sunday
is not a good idea.

00:58:44.740 --> 00:58:46.470
The most important thing about shift work

00:58:46.470 --> 00:58:49.170
is to stay consistent with your schedule.

00:58:49.170 --> 00:58:52.100
Now, I had a conversation
on an Instagram live

00:58:52.100 --> 00:58:56.010
with Samer Hattar, who's a neuroscientist

00:58:56.010 --> 00:58:57.670
at the National Institutes
of Mental Health,

00:58:57.670 --> 00:58:59.690
he's actually the head of
the chronobiology unit there.

00:58:59.690 --> 00:59:03.620
And he was really emphasizing
this point because shift work

00:59:03.620 --> 00:59:05.380
where people are doing
the so-called swing shift,

00:59:05.380 --> 00:59:07.040
where they're working
four days on one shift

00:59:07.040 --> 00:59:08.650
and four days on or another,

00:59:08.650 --> 00:59:11.590
is extremely detrimental to a
number of health parameters.

00:59:11.590 --> 00:59:14.930
It gets the cortisol
release from the adrenals

00:59:14.930 --> 00:59:16.280
really out of whack.

00:59:16.280 --> 00:59:18.880
And there're these cortisol spikes at

00:59:18.880 --> 00:59:21.570
various hours of the day,
it messes up learning,

00:59:21.570 --> 00:59:24.690
it really disrupts the
dopamine system and wellbeing.

00:59:24.690 --> 00:59:26.580
It is a serious, serious problem.

00:59:26.580 --> 00:59:29.640
So if you can negotiate with your employer

00:59:30.580 --> 00:59:34.230
to stay on the same shift
for two weeks at a time,

00:59:34.230 --> 00:59:35.860
that's going to be immensely beneficial

00:59:35.860 --> 00:59:36.800
and will help you offset

00:59:36.800 --> 00:59:39.000
a lot of the negative
effects of shift work.

00:59:39.920 --> 00:59:41.320
Now, I don't presume that

00:59:41.320 --> 00:59:43.290
all of you are going
to be able to do that.

00:59:43.290 --> 00:59:46.440
Some of you just don't
have that level of control.

00:59:46.440 --> 00:59:48.990
And of course, I want to acknowledge that

00:59:48.990 --> 00:59:51.550
shift workers are essential, right?

00:59:51.550 --> 00:59:53.490
Of course, first responders, firefighters,

00:59:53.490 --> 00:59:55.750
