sometimes with flecks of black or brown.

01:11:30.240 --> 01:11:34.760
And in the summer their
pelage changes to a color of

01:11:34.760 --> 01:11:38.453
you know, brown or red, some
other vastly different color.

01:11:39.650 --> 01:11:43.623
That shift is controlled
by light and by melatonin.

01:11:45.610 --> 01:11:48.720
This has an interesting
correlate in humans.

01:11:48.720 --> 01:11:52.670
So humans obviously have
different skin tones

01:11:52.670 --> 01:11:56.200
just genetically because
of the amount of melanin

01:11:56.200 --> 01:11:59.223
in one skin, depending
on genetic background.

01:12:00.240 --> 01:12:03.660
But of course sunlight will
increase the amount of melanin

01:12:03.660 --> 01:12:05.690
in the skin regardless, right?

01:12:05.690 --> 01:12:09.423
This is suntan, sunburn,
etc, bronzing, whatever.

01:12:12.290 --> 01:12:16.550
The whole system is wired
so that shifts in skin color

01:12:16.550 --> 01:12:20.950
and shifts in these cells
within the eye and melatonin

01:12:20.950 --> 01:12:22.480
are actually very closely linked.

01:12:22.480 --> 01:12:23.493
So here's the story.

01:12:24.910 --> 01:12:29.910
Many years ago, meaning about
10 years ago, 15 years ago,

01:12:30.240 --> 01:12:35.090
let's see it was 20 years ago, forgive me.

01:12:35.090 --> 01:12:37.290
A guy named Iggy Provencio

01:12:37.290 --> 01:12:42.260
who was running his own lab
at uniformed armed services,

01:12:42.260 --> 01:12:45.070
this is a standard biological laboratory,

01:12:45.070 --> 01:12:50.070
discovered that there
was an opsin in the eye

01:12:50.140 --> 01:12:51.290
in the cells of the eye

01:12:51.290 --> 01:12:54.700
that connect to the rest of
the brain called melanopsin.

01:12:54.700 --> 01:12:56.340
Melanopsin, as many of you now know

01:12:56.340 --> 01:12:59.833
is the opsin, it's like a
pigment, it absorbs light.

01:13:00.950 --> 01:13:03.720
It is the opsin that converts
light into electrical signals

01:13:03.720 --> 01:13:05.323
to then set the circadian clock.

01:13:07.110 --> 01:13:09.680
Iggy discovered melanopsin

01:13:09.680 --> 01:13:14.080
because it was similar in form

01:13:14.080 --> 01:13:18.560
to what was in frog melanophores.

01:13:18.560 --> 01:13:21.020
It was actually in the skin of frogs

01:13:21.020 --> 01:13:23.350
that allowed those frogs to go from

01:13:23.350 --> 01:13:26.030
pale white, when it was dark,

01:13:26.030 --> 01:13:28.310
for most of the 24 hour cycle,

01:13:28.310 --> 01:13:33.123
to pigmented green or brown for a frog.

01:13:34.100 --> 01:13:37.870
So there's this relationship
between the cells in our eye

01:13:37.870 --> 01:13:39.653
and the pigment cells of our skin.

01:13:40.580 --> 01:13:44.320
And we also know that in long
days, there's more breeding.

01:13:44.320 --> 01:13:45.153
How does that work?

01:13:45.153 --> 01:13:47.530
Well that's actually from dopamine

01:13:47.530 --> 01:13:51.340
triggering increases in
testosterone, mainly in males,

01:13:51.340 --> 01:13:53.700
and estrogen mainly in
females although of course,

01:13:53.700 --> 01:13:57.230
there's testosterone
estrogen in both sexes.

01:13:57.230 --> 01:14:01.470
So we have this kind of
pathway where it's light,

01:14:01.470 --> 01:14:03.270
increases in the melanin,

01:14:03.270 --> 01:14:05.690
dopamine and reproduction on the one hand

01:14:05.690 --> 01:14:08.133
and lack of light, melatonin,

01:14:09.140 --> 01:14:11.890
decreases in the darkness of skin,

01:14:11.890 --> 01:14:14.400
less melanin in the skin,

01:14:14.400 --> 01:14:16.320
or in the case of an animal with fur,

01:14:16.320 --> 01:14:18.803
white fur and no reproduction
on the other hand.

01:14:19.820 --> 01:14:24.820
And humans don't actually
shift their breeding patterns

01:14:25.380 --> 01:14:28.440
tremendously from long
days and short days,

01:14:28.440 --> 01:14:31.670
although there are some data
that there's some shifts.

01:14:31.670 --> 01:14:34.600
We also don't radically
change our skin color

01:14:34.600 --> 01:14:37.580
depending on how much
sunlight exposure we have.

01:14:37.580 --> 01:14:39.540
But the simple way to put this is,

01:14:39.540 --> 01:14:41.720
when days are long,

01:14:41.720 --> 01:14:43.420
there's a lot more dopamine

01:14:43.420 --> 01:14:44.800
and we feel really good

01:14:44.800 --> 01:14:48.000
and there's a lot more breeding
and breeding-like behavior.

01:14:48.000 --> 01:14:51.700
When days are short,
there's a lot less dopamine

01:14:51.700 --> 01:14:53.480
and a lot less breeding behavior

01:14:53.480 --> 01:14:57.690
because these pathways
are very highly conserved.

01:14:57.690 --> 01:15:00.960
Now what's interesting is that,

01:15:00.960 --> 01:15:03.480
as we've moved into a modern society

01:15:03.480 --> 01:15:06.270
where much of our waking days

01:15:06.270 --> 01:15:08.070
we are looking at screens, which is fine,

01:15:08.070 --> 01:15:09.440
'cause we're getting a
lot of light that way

01:15:09.440 --> 01:15:11.170
although not as much as sunlight.

01:15:11.170 --> 01:15:13.210
But also at night,

01:15:13.210 --> 01:15:15.550
we're getting a lot of light from screens.

01:15:15.550 --> 01:15:18.013
What's happened is all these path ways,

01:15:19.420 --> 01:15:23.090
melanin in the skin, turnover
of skin cells, dopamine,

01:15:23.090 --> 01:15:26.670
all of this stuff has
become completely disrupted.

01:15:26.670 --> 01:15:28.290
Now that's not to say
that we should go back

01:15:28.290 --> 01:15:30.650
to a time in which we didn't
use artificial lights.

01:15:30.650 --> 01:15:32.430
But I think the important thing to realize

01:15:32.430 --> 01:15:36.383
is that feeling good with
getting a lot of light,

01:15:37.610 --> 01:15:42.610
the relationship to dopamine
and melanin in the skin,

01:15:42.960 --> 01:15:46.490
and the good feelings of
getting light also on our skin

01:15:46.490 --> 01:15:48.030
provided you're not getting burned

01:15:48.030 --> 01:15:50.590
or you're not getting
excessive UV exposure,

01:15:50.590 --> 01:15:53.200
those are not just coincidences.

01:15:53.200 --> 01:15:55.440
Those are hard-wired biological mechanisms

01:15:55.440 --> 01:15:56.500
that exist in everybody

01:15:56.500 --> 01:16:00.093
regardless of how light or dark
your skin is to begin with.

01:16:01.310 --> 01:16:03.270
There's another point, which is important,

01:16:03.270 --> 01:16:05.800
which is that the dopamine system

01:16:05.800 --> 01:16:07.940
which is this feel-good molecule

01:16:07.940 --> 01:16:09.930
is very closely related

01:16:09.930 --> 01:16:12.730
to the testosterone and
estrogen in reproductive cycles.

01:16:12.730 --> 01:16:16.710
Remember melatonin inhibits
gonadotropin-releasing hormone,

01:16:16.710 --> 01:16:19.500
luteinizing hormone, and the
production of these hormones,

01:16:19.500 --> 01:16:21.560
and melatonin is the effector.

01:16:21.560 --> 01:16:24.490
It is the hormone of darkness.

01:16:24.490 --> 01:16:27.960
So, I just threw a lot of biology at you.

01:16:27.960 --> 01:16:30.850
And I'm not saying you're
like a Siberian hamster,

01:16:30.850 --> 01:16:32.840
at least not in ways that I'm aware of.

01:16:32.840 --> 01:16:36.160
I'm not saying that your pelage
color is going to change.

01:16:36.160 --> 01:16:37.870
Actually the reason people go gray

01:16:37.870 --> 01:16:40.343
is because when you're really
stressed, did you know this,

01:16:40.343 --> 01:16:42.480
that when you're really stressed,

01:16:42.480 --> 01:16:44.720
there's an increase in the nerve fibers

01:16:44.720 --> 01:16:48.360
that release adrenaline
to the hair follicle

01:16:48.360 --> 01:16:52.890
and that activates peroxide
groups in the hair follicle

01:16:52.890 --> 01:16:55.640
that cause the hair to
actually go gray or white.

01:16:55.640 --> 01:16:58.790
So actually stress does make
your hair gray or white.

01:16:58.790 --> 01:16:59.883
Aging does it too.

01:17:02.060 --> 01:17:03.180
That was a brief aside,

01:17:03.180 --> 01:17:05.390
but for those of you
that are interested in

01:17:05.390 --> 01:17:07.680
the relationship between
light and skin tone

01:17:07.680 --> 01:17:09.100
and all that kind of stuff,
I thought you might find it

01:17:09.100 --> 01:17:10.770
interesting that the cells in your eye

01:17:10.770 --> 01:17:15.400
are a lot like these skin
cells in frogs or in animals

01:17:15.400 --> 01:17:20.390
that shift their entire color
and sometimes metamorphosize.

01:17:20.390 --> 01:17:21.810
You know, there are some
species that literally

01:17:21.810 --> 01:17:23.520
change shape in their reproductive organs.

01:17:23.520 --> 01:17:25.970
In fact, if that wasn't weird enough,

01:17:25.970 --> 01:17:27.730
when I was in graduate school at Berkeley,

01:17:27.730 --> 01:17:30.920
there was another graduate
student studying a species

01:17:30.920 --> 01:17:35.350
of hermaphroditic mole, right,
those little things that dig,

01:17:35.350 --> 01:17:37.790
hermaphrodite mole that would change

01:17:37.790 --> 01:17:41.950
from having ovaries to
testes and back again

01:17:41.950 --> 01:17:43.920
depending on day life.

01:17:43.920 --> 01:17:46.193
Super cool, super different,

01:17:47.420 --> 01:17:50.033
and wild biological mechanism.

01:17:50.990 --> 01:17:52.910
If you're wondering how
those animals reproduce

01:17:52.910 --> 01:17:55.050
they actually adjust the
numbers of males and females

01:17:55.050 --> 01:17:56.810
depending on the density
of males and females.

01:17:56.810 --> 01:17:58.453
So if there are too many males,

01:17:59.320 --> 01:18:02.960
some of the males turn
their testes into ovaries.

01:18:02.960 --> 01:18:04.010
And if there're too many females,

01:18:04.010 --> 01:18:05.690
they turn their ovaries into testes.

01:18:05.690 --> 01:18:08.680
They actually are true
hermaphroditic animals

01:18:08.680 --> 01:18:11.810
as opposed to as pseudo
hermaphrodite animals.

01:18:11.810 --> 01:18:13.980
Okay, let's get back on track.

01:18:13.980 --> 01:18:17.200
Let's talk about the animal
that most of you care about

01:18:17.200 --> 01:18:18.603
which is the human animal.

01:18:19.690 --> 01:18:22.150
New parents and babies.

01:18:22.150 --> 01:18:23.630
All right, as I mentioned earlier,

01:18:23.630 --> 01:18:28.470
melatonin is not cyclic,
it's not cycling in babies,

01:18:28.470 --> 01:18:29.610
it's more phasic.

01:18:29.610 --> 01:18:32.740
It's being released at a
kind of a constant level.

01:18:32.740 --> 01:18:35.950
And babies tend to be smaller
than adults, they are.

01:18:35.950 --> 01:18:38.780
And so those concentrations
of melatonin are very high.

01:18:38.780 --> 01:18:40.820
As the baby grows, those concentrations

01:18:40.820 --> 01:18:42.683
per unit volume are going to go down.

01:18:44.240 --> 01:18:47.370
Babies are not born with a
typical sleep wake cycle.

01:18:47.370 --> 01:18:49.000
And now all the parents are saying,

01:18:49.000 --> 01:18:50.600
tell me something I didn't know.

01:18:51.730 --> 01:18:55.470
They also have, and I really
want to emphasize this,

01:18:55.470 --> 01:18:59.820
they also have much more
sensitive optics of the eye.

01:18:59.820 --> 01:19:02.220
So a number of people
have asked me, you know,

01:19:02.220 --> 01:19:04.820
should I be exposing my baby to sunlight?

01:19:04.820 --> 01:19:06.280
You don't want to avoid sunlight,

01:19:06.280 --> 01:19:08.290
but their eyes are very sensitive,

01:19:08.290 --> 01:19:10.610
the optics of their eyes
aren't quite developed

01:19:10.610 --> 01:19:14.530
so much so that you know when
you look at a newborn baby

01:19:14.530 --> 01:19:16.760
and they look a little glassy-eyed

01:19:16.760 --> 01:19:17.640
and they're kind of looking through you

01:19:17.640 --> 01:19:19.150
or even a young child.

01:19:19.150 --> 01:19:21.620
A lot of people think
that they're seeing you

01:19:21.620 --> 01:19:23.070
the way that you're seeing them.

01:19:23.070 --> 01:19:27.800
Hate to break it to you, but
if you ever can just google

01:19:28.930 --> 01:19:32.290
visual image of a like a one month old.

01:19:32.290 --> 01:19:34.400
The optics of their eyes are so poor

01:19:34.400 --> 01:19:35.990
that you're a cloudy image.

01:19:35.990 --> 01:19:38.220
They're not seeing your fine detail.

01:19:38.220 --> 01:19:39.883
As the optics get better,

01:19:40.750 --> 01:19:43.330
then they will see you
with more and more clarity.

01:19:43.330 --> 01:19:45.090
But a lot of that is clearing of the lens

01:19:45.090 --> 01:19:48.910
and some of the other aqueous
features of the newborn eye,

01:19:48.910 --> 01:19:50.513
they don't see very well.

01:19:51.350 --> 01:19:54.290
But they also don't have such great ways

01:19:54.290 --> 01:19:55.740
of adjusting to bright light.

01:19:55.740 --> 01:19:58.370
And so babies have a natural
aversion to bright lights.

01:19:58.370 --> 01:20:00.310
So you really want to avoid

01:20:00.310 --> 01:20:02.400
trying to use sunlight
or really bright light

01:20:02.400 --> 01:20:04.300
in the same way that
you would for an adult

01:20:04.300 --> 01:20:06.123
on a young baby or child.

01:20:06.960 --> 01:20:10.170
As children get older however,

01:20:10.170 --> 01:20:13.250
melatonin does start to
become slightly more cyclic,

01:20:13.250 --> 01:20:14.460
slightly more cycled,

01:20:14.460 --> 01:20:17.360
and their body temperature
rhythms also start to

01:20:17.360 --> 01:20:20.960
fall into a more regular,
not quite 24 hour rhythm,

01:20:20.960 --> 01:20:22.500
they're more of these ultradian rhythms.

01:20:22.500 --> 01:20:26.740
So in episode, I think it was
one or two of the podcast,

01:20:26.740 --> 01:20:28.900
or maybe both, we talked
about these 90 minute

01:20:28.900 --> 01:20:33.090
so-called ultradian rhythms,
where every 90 minutes

01:20:33.090 --> 01:20:37.660
babies are going through a
cycle of body temperature

01:20:37.660 --> 01:20:39.190
and some other hormonal features.

01:20:39.190 --> 01:20:42.140
I mean, so much is
changing in their system.

01:20:42.140 --> 01:20:45.690
So what to do if a child isn't sleeping?

01:20:45.690 --> 01:20:49.490
You can use phases of
darkness and phases of light

01:20:49.490 --> 01:20:50.940
but they're going to have to be shortened

01:20:50.940 --> 01:20:52.460
in order to try and encourage sleep

01:20:52.460 --> 01:20:53.640
when you want the child to sleep.

01:20:53.640 --> 01:20:55.720
It's not that they're
just not going to fall

01:20:55.720 --> 01:20:57.570
into an adult-like regime

01:20:57.570 --> 01:21:00.150
of a temperature minimum
and a temperature maximum.

01:21:00.150 --> 01:21:01.730
Their temperature minimums and maximums

01:21:01.730 --> 01:21:03.840
are fluctuating much more quickly.

01:21:03.840 --> 01:21:05.433
And it varies tremendously.

01:21:06.690 --> 01:21:08.690
Actually there's an interesting literature

01:21:08.690 --> 01:21:10.090
of whether or not they have siblings,

01:21:10.090 --> 01:21:11.050
whether or not they're twins,

01:21:11.050 --> 01:21:13.160
whether or not they're
in a nursery environment,

01:21:13.160 --> 01:21:14.850
whether or not they're alone,

01:21:14.850 --> 01:21:16.173
hopefully the baby's not alone,
but you know what I mean,

01:21:16.173 --> 01:21:17.640
that they're sleeping alone in a room

01:21:17.640 --> 01:21:19.670
while you're in the other room.

01:21:19.670 --> 01:21:21.660
There are a couple of
things that seem to help

01:21:21.660 --> 01:21:23.600
which is getting the overall environment

01:21:23.600 --> 01:21:25.220
into a 24 hour schedule.

01:21:25.220 --> 01:21:27.850
So having the room slightly colder,

01:21:27.850 --> 01:21:30.000
obviously you want babies
to be nice and cozy,

01:21:30.000 --> 01:21:32.790
slightly colder when you
would like them to be asleep,

01:21:32.790 --> 01:21:34.140
slightly warmer for the times

01:21:34.140 --> 01:21:35.150
you would like them to be awake.

01:21:35.150 --> 01:21:38.053
Babies tend to run pretty hot anyway.

01:21:39.680 --> 01:21:43.040
And obviously you want to be very careful

01:21:43.040 --> 01:21:47.253
about avoiding all extremes
of temperature, cold or hot.

01:21:48.250 --> 01:21:51.010
So if they're going through
these 90 minute cycles,

01:21:51.010 --> 01:21:52.310
you're going to have to adjust

01:21:52.310 --> 01:21:53.860
to those 90 minute cycles as well.

01:21:53.860 --> 01:21:55.840
So then people say, well, that's
not going to help me at all

01:21:55.840 --> 01:21:57.330
because how do I deal with the fact

01:21:57.330 --> 01:21:59.480
that I need to be up
every 90 minutes at night?

01:21:59.480 --> 01:22:02.200
There are a couple tools
that can be helpful.

01:22:02.200 --> 01:22:06.360
The first one is going to
be to try and understand

01:22:06.360 --> 01:22:09.680
the relationship between
calm and deep sleep.

01:22:09.680 --> 01:22:11.750
So the autonomic nervous system

01:22:11.750 --> 01:22:14.300
can put us into states of panic,

01:22:14.300 --> 01:22:16.750
where that's kind of seesaw
of autonomic alertness,

01:22:16.750 --> 01:22:18.080
goes all the way to panic.

01:22:18.080 --> 01:22:20.590
Or it can be alertness, or it
can be alert and calm, right?

01:22:20.590 --> 01:22:23.170
So there's a range
there, it's a continuum.

01:22:23.170 --> 01:22:26.070
It can also be that you're in deep sleep,

01:22:26.070 --> 01:22:27.750
so the other end of the seesaw is way up

01:22:27.750 --> 01:22:30.160
or you're your in light sleep
or you're kind of sleepy,

01:22:30.160 --> 01:22:32.163
or you're just feeling kind of relaxed.

01:22:33.200 --> 01:22:36.320
Perhaps the most important thing

01:22:36.320 --> 01:22:39.550
if you're having to map to a baby schedule

01:22:39.550 --> 01:22:41.120
in order to make sure that they're getting

01:22:41.120 --> 01:22:44.370
changings, and nursing, etc,
at the appropriate times,

01:22:44.370 --> 01:22:48.370
is to try and maintain,

01:22:48.370 --> 01:22:51.860
if you can't sleep or you
can't sleep continuously,

01:22:51.860 --> 01:22:56.090
to try and maintain your
autonomic nervous system

01:22:56.090 --> 01:22:58.100
in a place where you're not

01:22:58.100 --> 01:23:00.450
going into heightened states of alertness

01:23:00.450 --> 01:23:03.140
when you would ideally be sleeping.

01:23:03.140 --> 01:23:06.110
Now, I realize that this
could be translated to

01:23:06.110 --> 01:23:07.930
try and stay calm while
you're sleep deprived,

01:23:07.930 --> 01:23:10.030
which is very hard for people to do.

01:23:10.030 --> 01:23:11.410
But this is where

01:23:11.410 --> 01:23:13.760
the non-sleep deep rest
protocols surface again

01:23:13.760 --> 01:23:16.160
and can potentially be very beneficial

01:23:16.160 --> 01:23:19.970
for people to be able to
recover, not necessarily sleep,

01:23:19.970 --> 01:23:21.680
but for them to maintain

01:23:21.680 --> 01:23:24.030
a certain amount of autonomic regulation.

01:23:24.030 --> 01:23:25.100
So what would this look like?

01:23:25.100 --> 01:23:27.240
This would look like, the baby goes down,

01:23:27.240 --> 01:23:29.610
maybe it's only going to
go down for 45 minutes.

01:23:29.610 --> 01:23:33.510
If you can capture sleep, capture sleep.

01:23:33.510 --> 01:23:35.990
There are some data showing
what's called polyphasic sleep.

01:23:35.990 --> 01:23:39.020
If you can sleep in 45
minute increments or batches,

01:23:39.020 --> 01:23:40.650
even if it's spread throughout the day

01:23:40.650 --> 01:23:42.160
with periods of wakefulness in between,

01:23:42.160 --> 01:23:43.270
as miserable as that sound,

01:23:43.270 --> 01:23:44.960
there are actually some adults that have

01:23:44.960 --> 01:23:46.110
deliberately employed that,

01:23:46.110 --> 01:23:49.420
who don't have children for
the sake of work productivity.

01:23:49.420 --> 01:23:50.710
And it does tend to reduce

01:23:50.710 --> 01:23:53.600
the total overall amount
of sleep that you need.

01:23:53.600 --> 01:23:55.810
It is a very hard schedule
for most people to maintain

01:23:55.810 --> 01:23:57.590
but if you have a baby, the
baby may be throwing you

01:23:57.590 --> 01:23:58.880
into that kind of schedule anyway.

01:23:58.880 --> 01:24:02.070
So if you can get 45 minutes
sleep while they sleep, great.

01:24:02.070 --> 01:24:03.990
If you can get another
45 minutes after waking

01:24:03.990 --> 01:24:05.840
and then they go back
down to sleep, great.

01:24:05.840 --> 01:24:07.840
So as many phases of sleep as you can get.

01:24:07.840 --> 01:24:09.650
But if you can't sleep

01:24:09.650 --> 01:24:12.520
the data on non-sleep
deep rest type protocols

01:24:12.520 --> 01:24:15.380
does show that at least
from a neurochemical level,

01:24:15.380 --> 01:24:16.860
I want to be clear what that means,

01:24:16.860 --> 01:24:20.470
reset of things like dopamine
levels in the basal ganglia

01:24:20.470 --> 01:24:23.700
measured by things like positron
emission tomography, etc.

01:24:23.700 --> 01:24:26.690
Those things tend to reset
themselves pretty well

01:24:26.690 --> 01:24:29.160
if you can access these deep rest state.

01:24:29.160 --> 01:24:32.310
So that means not being alert

01:24:32.310 --> 01:24:34.230
throughout the entire time
that the baby is sleeping.

01:24:34.230 --> 01:24:37.470
Trying to sort of mirror
the baby's sleep cycle

01:24:37.470 --> 01:24:39.130
which can be brutal for certain people,

01:24:39.130 --> 01:24:40.870
and especially if you're
trying to prepare meals

01:24:40.870 --> 01:24:41.703
and do all these things.

01:24:41.703 --> 01:24:42.536
So I do recognize

01:24:42.536 --> 01:24:43.880
that there are a lot of
constraints on parenting

01:24:43.880 --> 01:24:46.400
not just mapping on your
baby's sleep schedule.

01:24:46.400 --> 01:24:51.000
As children approach ages
one, two, three, four,

01:24:51.000 --> 01:24:54.480
that's when certainly the
optics of the eyes have improved

01:24:54.480 --> 01:24:56.480
but you don't want to
damage the eyes of course,

01:24:56.480 --> 01:24:58.010
with very bright light.

01:24:58.010 --> 01:25:00.730
They are much more sensitive even until

01:25:00.730 --> 01:25:02.993
they're kind of 10, 11 years old.

01:25:04.110 --> 01:25:06.480
And we'll talk about vision
in children in a moment.

01:25:06.480 --> 01:25:11.040
But trying to get longer
and longer batches of sleep

01:25:11.040 --> 01:25:13.270
through, hopefully not through the use

01:25:13.270 --> 01:25:15.480
of administering melatonin to the kids

01:25:15.480 --> 01:25:17.780
'cause that's what I talked about before

01:25:17.780 --> 01:25:19.580
why that could potentially be detrimental

01:25:19.580 --> 01:25:21.140
talk about that with your doctor.

01:25:21.140 --> 01:25:25.880
But more so trying to get
longer blocks of sleep

01:25:25.880 --> 01:25:28.010
that map onto these ultradian cycles.

01:25:28.010 --> 01:25:30.610
So it would be better
off to get a three hour,

01:25:30.610 --> 01:25:34.300
like two-90 minute cycles,
than a four hour batch of sleep

01:25:34.300 --> 01:25:36.860
because waking up in the middle
of those ultradian cycles

01:25:36.860 --> 01:25:39.470
can just be brutal for parent and kid.

01:25:39.470 --> 01:25:42.700
So if one can't get a full six or 10,

01:25:42.700 --> 01:25:44.650
or some kids should even
be sleeping 12 hours

01:25:44.650 --> 01:25:45.830
when they're growing quickly,

01:25:45.830 --> 01:25:47.950
trying to get batches of sleep

01:25:47.950 --> 01:25:51.050
even if they're fractured
throughout the 24 hour cycle

01:25:51.050 --> 01:25:54.020
that are matched more to
these 90 minute cycles,

01:25:54.020 --> 01:25:56.650
meaning maybe one ultradian
cycle of 90 minutes,

01:25:56.650 --> 01:26:01.100
or two back to back, or
three back to back to back.

01:26:01.100 --> 01:26:02.580
That's going to be better than waking up

01:26:02.580 --> 01:26:04.270
in the middle of an ultradian cycle.

01:26:04.270 --> 01:26:06.910
It's just going to set
any number of other things

01:26:06.910 --> 01:26:10.790
in a better direction than
were you to try to say,

01:26:10.790 --> 01:26:15.070
just enforce or force a full
eight or 10 hours of sleep.

01:26:15.070 --> 01:26:17.410
That's at least what the literature shows.

01:26:17.410 --> 01:26:19.200
Some kids sleep great through the night,

01:26:19.200 --> 01:26:20.970
starting at a very
young age, others don't.

01:26:20.970 --> 01:26:22.460
I typically hear from people

01:26:22.460 --> 01:26:24.350
who are struggling tremendously,

01:26:24.350 --> 01:26:26.370
they're losing their mind understandably,

01:26:26.370 --> 01:26:29.520
because they're not sleeping,
their kid's not sleeping and,

01:26:29.520 --> 01:26:31.330
or their kid is sleeping
for such brief periods.

01:26:31.330 --> 01:26:33.700
So in other words, try
and access deep calm

01:26:33.700 --> 01:26:35.960
if you can't sleep, try and
access sleep, if you can sleep

01:26:35.960 --> 01:26:37.280
even if it's fractured.

01:26:37.280 --> 01:26:39.470
And then you say, well, what
about all the sunlight viewing

01:26:39.470 --> 01:26:40.733
and the exercise stuff?

01:26:41.820 --> 01:26:46.160
When sleep is really, really dismantled,

01:26:46.160 --> 01:26:49.470
meaning it's happening in
various times of day or night,

01:26:49.470 --> 01:26:52.323
that's especially, at those times

01:26:52.323 --> 01:26:54.990
it's going to be especially
important for the parent

01:26:54.990 --> 01:26:56.650
to get morning and evening sunlight

01:26:56.650 --> 01:26:59.560
because your circadian clock
is going into a tailspin

01:26:59.560 --> 01:27:01.520
and it basically wants
to anchor to something.

01:27:01.520 --> 01:27:05.130
So you want to give it two
anchors, morning and evening light.

01:27:05.130 --> 01:27:07.590
Okay, so this is rather different

01:27:07.590 --> 01:27:09.210
than what I described for shift work,

01:27:09.210 --> 01:27:10.820
this is when things are really chaotic

01:27:10.820 --> 01:27:12.110
and you're just not able to sleep.

01:27:12.110 --> 01:27:13.640
Similar circumstances can arise

01:27:13.640 --> 01:27:15.540
if you're taking care of
a very sick loved one,

01:27:15.540 --> 01:27:16.890
you're up all night.

01:27:16.890 --> 01:27:19.460
Try and stay calm using NSDR protocols,

01:27:19.460 --> 01:27:22.660
I know it's harder to do than to say,

01:27:22.660 --> 01:27:24.940
but those protocols are
there, they're free,

01:27:24.940 --> 01:27:26.660
there's research to support them.

01:27:26.660 --> 01:27:28.650
Try and get sleep whenever you can

01:27:28.650 --> 01:27:31.950
but also try to get morning sunlight

01:27:31.950 --> 01:27:34.200
and evening sunlight
in your eyes if you can

01:27:34.200 --> 01:27:37.383
and if you can't get that,
use artificial light, okay?

01:27:38.490 --> 01:27:39.990
What about later life?

01:27:39.990 --> 01:27:42.190
So kids now, adolescents, teens,

01:27:42.190 --> 01:27:46.300
it is true that teens have
a tendency to wake up later

01:27:46.300 --> 01:27:47.730
and go to sleep later.

01:27:47.730 --> 01:27:50.610
In part, just because
they're sleeping a lot more.

01:27:50.610 --> 01:27:52.820
They're churning out
gonadotropin-releasing hormone

01:27:52.820 --> 01:27:53.880
and luteinizing hormone.

01:27:53.880 --> 01:27:55.480
Their whole bodies are changing.

01:27:56.370 --> 01:27:58.460
I don't know whether or
not people realize this,

01:27:58.460 --> 01:28:00.520
but the fastest rate of aging

01:28:00.520 --> 01:28:03.513
that any of us will
ever undergo is puberty.

01:28:04.370 --> 01:28:06.220
That is the fastest rate of aging.

01:28:06.220 --> 01:28:08.650
And so there's a huge number
of biological processes

01:28:08.650 --> 01:28:10.200
that are happening during puberty,

01:28:10.200 --> 01:28:11.870
probably devote a whole episode

01:28:11.870 --> 01:28:16.690
to puberty as a fascinating
aspect to the life course

01:28:16.690 --> 01:28:19.390
but it is accelerated period of aging.

01:28:19.390 --> 01:28:21.510
And the circadian clock mechanisms

01:28:21.510 --> 01:28:24.530
sometimes are very intact,

01:28:24.530 --> 01:28:25.950
and sometimes they're a little dismantled

01:28:25.950 --> 01:28:27.730
and going through some change,

01:28:27.730 --> 01:28:31.300
but prioritize the duration of sleep

01:28:31.300 --> 01:28:33.070
for adolescents and teens.

01:28:33.070 --> 01:28:35.010
Now, if that means they're
sleeping until 2:00 PM,

01:28:35.010 --> 01:28:36.730
and then waking up and
then they're up all night,

01:28:36.730 --> 01:28:38.560
the up all night part can become a problem

01:28:38.560 --> 01:28:39.870
especially with all the devices,

01:28:39.870 --> 01:28:43.270
texting in their rooms
or playing video games.

01:28:43.270 --> 01:28:45.110
Morning and evening
sunlight would be ideal

01:28:45.110 --> 01:28:46.530
but some kids are just going to sleep

01:28:46.530 --> 01:28:47.840
through the morning sunlight.

01:28:47.840 --> 01:28:49.670
However, if you were to
measure their temperature,

01:28:49.670 --> 01:28:52.200
what you would find is that
their temperature minimum

01:28:52.200 --> 01:28:54.150
would come later in the morning.

01:28:54.150 --> 01:28:57.150
It's not going to be 8:00 AM.

01:28:57.150 --> 01:28:58.680
It's going to be maybe even 10:00 AM,

01:28:58.680 --> 01:29:01.230
if they're sleeping until 11 or 12.

01:29:01.230 --> 01:29:03.900
Or it might be 8:00 AM if
they're sleeping until 10.

01:29:03.900 --> 01:29:05.540
Remember temperature minimum is two hours

01:29:05.540 --> 01:29:08.360
before your average
waking time, typically.

01:29:08.360 --> 01:29:11.260
So in teens, it maximizes
the total amount of sleep.

01:29:11.260 --> 01:29:13.980
Try and get regular sunlight
either in the morning

01:29:13.980 --> 01:29:15.600
or in the evening or both.

01:29:15.600 --> 01:29:17.280
But if they're sleeping
through the morning sunrise,

01:29:17.280 --> 01:29:20.480
that's probably not as much of an issue,

01:29:20.480 --> 01:29:22.320
waking them up and depriving them of sleep

01:29:22.320 --> 01:29:24.500
is probably worse because their T-min,

01:29:24.500 --> 01:29:28.020
their temperature minimum,
is actually falling later.

01:29:28.020 --> 01:29:30.790
So their circadian dead
zone is later, etc.

01:29:30.790 --> 01:29:32.770
So I think with adolescents and teens

01:29:32.770 --> 01:29:35.970
it makes sense to kind of give
them a little bit more rope

01:29:35.970 --> 01:29:39.090
in terms of allowing them some leeway

01:29:39.090 --> 01:29:40.220
to adjust their own schedule.

01:29:40.220 --> 01:29:42.240
Some schools are even
starting classes later

01:29:42.240 --> 01:29:45.120
on the basis of some very good biology

01:29:45.120 --> 01:29:46.697
to support this late shifted rhythm

01:29:46.697 --> 01:29:48.513
and this extended sleep phase.

01:29:49.940 --> 01:29:53.320
There are data from Dr. Jamie Zeitzer,

01:29:53.320 --> 01:29:54.890
Department of Psychiatry
and Behavioral Sciences,

01:29:54.890 --> 01:29:57.700
and others at Stanford, showing
that turning on the lights

01:29:57.700 --> 01:29:59.840
in the room of a teen before they wake up

01:30:00.730 --> 01:30:03.680
helps them get more sleep
the subsequent night,

01:30:03.680 --> 01:30:04.640
it also tricks them

01:30:04.640 --> 01:30:06.040
into going to sleep a little bit earlier.

01:30:06.040 --> 01:30:09.160
But it gives them about 45
minutes more of deep sleep.

01:30:09.160 --> 01:30:11.020
And that's been shown statistically,

01:30:11.020 --> 01:30:13.370
total sleep time increases as well.

01:30:13.370 --> 01:30:15.170
If they're hiding under the
covers, that's not going to work,

01:30:15.170 --> 01:30:17.090
but their eyes don't have to be open.

01:30:17.090 --> 01:30:18.420
I know a few parents now

01:30:18.420 --> 01:30:19.590
that are coming in with a flashlight

01:30:19.590 --> 01:30:22.800
and flashing their kids over their eyelids

01:30:22.800 --> 01:30:24.980
before they wake up in hopes
of getting this to work,

01:30:24.980 --> 01:30:27.360
some have told me this is working.

01:30:27.360 --> 01:30:29.713
That's not part of a standard study.

01:30:30.780 --> 01:30:35.070
But it does seem to work
because, now you should know why,

01:30:35.070 --> 01:30:37.230
because if light's getting
through the eyelids,

01:30:37.230 --> 01:30:40.390
and it's say 8:00 AM and
the kid is still asleep

01:30:40.390 --> 01:30:41.830
and they're going to wake up at 10,

01:30:41.830 --> 01:30:43.110
you're giving them light

01:30:43.990 --> 01:30:47.370
just after or around
their temperature minimum,

01:30:47.370 --> 01:30:50.170
which is going to make them
want to go to sleep earlier.

01:30:50.170 --> 01:30:51.590
And in the case of teens,

01:30:51.590 --> 01:30:53.050
for some reason we don't quite understand,

01:30:53.050 --> 01:30:55.810
sleep longer, about 45 minutes longer,

01:30:55.810 --> 01:30:57.330
spend more time in deep sleep.

01:30:57.330 --> 01:30:59.480
Adults can do this too, if
you can persuade someone

01:30:59.480 --> 01:31:00.700
or put your lights on timer

01:31:00.700 --> 01:31:03.000
for lights to go on before you wake up,

01:31:03.000 --> 01:31:06.230
that's really going to help
you wake up earlier, okay.

01:31:06.230 --> 01:31:07.780
So if you're starting to hear

01:31:07.780 --> 01:31:11.210
some themes are really
resounding over and over again,

01:31:11.210 --> 01:31:12.993
that should be reassuring to you, right.

01:31:12.993 --> 01:31:15.780
That these are core mechanisms.

01:31:15.780 --> 01:31:18.740
Fortunately, there aren't
1,000 different mechanisms.

01:31:18.740 --> 01:31:21.343
Now in the elderly,

01:31:22.190 --> 01:31:25.380
there's a real tendency to
want to go to sleep very early

01:31:25.380 --> 01:31:27.330
and wake up very early.

01:31:27.330 --> 01:31:31.240
And people should talk to their physician.

01:31:31.240 --> 01:31:33.850
There is some evidence
that melatonin levels

01:31:33.850 --> 01:31:36.230
and patterns of melatonin secretion

01:31:36.230 --> 01:31:39.690
can become a little
chaotic in elderly folks.

01:31:39.690 --> 01:31:40.690
What do I mean by elderly?

01:31:40.690 --> 01:31:41.590
Well, it's going to differ.

01:31:41.590 --> 01:31:43.010
Rates of aging differ, right?

01:31:43.010 --> 01:31:47.240
You see some 65 year olds
that are struggling to move

01:31:47.240 --> 01:31:50.870
and seem much older than
some 65 year olds that are,

01:31:50.870 --> 01:31:54.170
you know, still hustling
around and have tons of energy.

01:31:54.170 --> 01:31:55.140
There's a lot of variation,

01:31:55.140 --> 01:31:58.770
some of it's genetic, some
of it's lifestyle factors,

01:31:58.770 --> 01:32:00.740
you know, it really varies.

01:32:00.740 --> 01:32:03.500
Certainly lifestyle factors
can play an important role

01:32:03.500 --> 01:32:04.693
in rates of aging.

01:32:06.110 --> 01:32:09.820
I think that the most prominent results

01:32:09.820 --> 01:32:13.760
from sleep and circadian
rhythms in the elderly are

01:32:13.760 --> 01:32:15.840
they need to get as much natural light,

01:32:15.840 --> 01:32:16.990
even if it's through windows.

01:32:16.990 --> 01:32:19.230
I realize that some elderly folks

01:32:19.230 --> 01:32:20.770
can't get outside as easily.

01:32:20.770 --> 01:32:22.020
It's not safe for them to do it,

01:32:22.020 --> 01:32:23.993
they can't move around as easily.

01:32:25.130 --> 01:32:26.960
Exercise can come in various forms

01:32:26.960 --> 01:32:29.420
for people that can't get outside

01:32:29.420 --> 01:32:32.120
and get a ton of sunlight
by jogging or cycling.

01:32:32.120 --> 01:32:33.370
If they're not able to do that,

01:32:33.370 --> 01:32:35.860
light through window in that
case, open window ideally,

01:32:35.860 --> 01:32:37.750
but for temperature reasons, etc,

01:32:37.750 --> 01:32:39.550
sometimes the window has to be closed.

01:32:39.550 --> 01:32:40.950
Getting people near that window

01:32:40.950 --> 01:32:43.610
and away from artificial
light early in the day,

01:32:43.610 --> 01:32:46.780
and away from artificial
lights during the night phase

01:32:46.780 --> 01:32:49.480
can have a tremendous effect.

01:32:49.480 --> 01:32:52.240
And in the elderly that's when melatonin

01:32:52.240 --> 01:32:55.220
might be a viable option.

01:32:55.220 --> 01:32:57.050
And this should be discussed
with a physician, of course,

01:32:57.050 --> 01:33:00.950
but you know, you're way
past the puberty time point.

01:33:00.950 --> 01:33:04.337
In most cases, people who
are in their 70s, and 80s,

01:33:04.337 --> 01:33:06.000
and 90s, are not churning out

01:33:06.000 --> 01:33:08.960
a lot of GnRH and luteinizing
hormone to begin with.

01:33:08.960 --> 01:33:10.700
And that's where struggles

01:33:10.700 --> 01:33:12.980
with falling asleep and staying asleep,

01:33:12.980 --> 01:33:14.190
all the same parameters

01:33:14.190 --> 01:33:17.340
and things we've described
before still apply,

01:33:17.340 --> 01:33:19.600
light, exercise, temperature, etc,

01:33:19.600 --> 01:33:22.990
but that's where melatonin
might be of greatest benefit.

01:33:22.990 --> 01:33:24.730
And again, I'm not pushing melatonin here

01:33:24.730 --> 01:33:26.240
but I think for elderly folks

01:33:26.240 --> 01:33:28.060
who are having trouble
falling and staying asleep,

01:33:28.060 --> 01:33:29.763
that might be worthwhile.

01:33:31.150 --> 01:33:34.820
There are, and I should
just also mention that

01:33:34.820 --> 01:33:37.360
regular schedule for
folks that are elderly

01:33:37.360 --> 01:33:40.900
and as much natural
light as safely possible,

01:33:40.900 --> 01:33:43.810
those are going to be the key levers

01:33:43.810 --> 01:33:46.203
for adjusting sleep in
circadian schedules.

01:33:47.600 --> 01:33:49.480
I've mentioned before
in previous podcasts,

01:33:49.480 --> 01:33:52.440
other supplements besides melatonin.

01:33:52.440 --> 01:33:54.717
And some of those supplements
are quite good for sleep.

01:33:54.717 --> 01:33:56.640
You know, I'm not a supplement pusher,

01:33:56.640 --> 01:34:00.313
I am somebody who takes
supplements, I believe in them,

01:34:01.190 --> 01:34:03.880
some have worked for me some
have not worked as well,

01:34:03.880 --> 01:34:07.850
but I certainly believe in
getting the behaviors right.

01:34:07.850 --> 01:34:11.040
Whether or not it's NSDR
protocols, viewing natural light,

01:34:11.040 --> 01:34:15.800
exercise, hot baths, or cold
showers, or what have you,

01:34:15.800 --> 01:34:18.160
behavioral protocols first.

01:34:18.160 --> 01:34:19.710
There are some supplements that

01:34:19.710 --> 01:34:21.000
I've mentioned in previous podcasts

01:34:21.000 --> 01:34:22.630
but I've seemed to get a
lot of questions about.

01:34:22.630 --> 01:34:24.760
So I just want to take a couple
minutes and just talk about

01:34:24.760 --> 01:34:26.850
some of the supplements
that can be beneficial

01:34:26.850 --> 01:34:30.870
for helping turning off
thinking, accessing deeper sleep,

01:34:30.870 --> 01:34:33.910
and even being able to
compact your sleep schedule

01:34:33.910 --> 01:34:35.240
into a shorter period of hours,

01:34:35.240 --> 01:34:37.640
meaning getting by well with less sleep.

01:34:37.640 --> 01:34:39.600
People take a lot of sleeping pills.

01:34:39.600 --> 01:34:42.320
I'm not going to tell people
not to take sleeping pills.

01:34:42.320 --> 01:34:44.583
They can be very
problematic, habit-forming,

01:34:45.510 --> 01:34:49.410
high side-effect incidents in many cases,

01:34:49.410 --> 01:34:51.700
some people can handle them just fine.

01:34:51.700 --> 01:34:54.380
Again, I'm no physician,

01:34:54.380 --> 01:34:55.637
I'm not prescribing anything.

01:34:55.637 --> 01:34:58.280
I'm a professor, so I
profess a lot of things

01:34:58.280 --> 01:34:59.830
some of which are my opinion.

01:34:59.830 --> 01:35:02.100
Although, if you look at
the scientific literature,

01:35:02.100 --> 01:35:04.710
there are some impressive data around some

01:35:04.710 --> 01:35:06.820
non-prescription drug type supplements

01:35:06.820 --> 01:35:09.510
that have fairly high safety margins

01:35:09.510 --> 01:35:10.343
that you might consider

01:35:10.343 --> 01:35:11.940
but you should talk to your doctor always

01:35:11.940 --> 01:35:13.750
before adding or taking anything

01:35:13.750 --> 01:35:15.740
out of your health regimes, right?

01:35:15.740 --> 01:35:17.470
Your health is not my responsibility,

01:35:17.470 --> 01:35:20.220
it's your responsibility,
so be a stringent filter.

01:35:20.220 --> 01:35:23.210
Along those lines, one of the
most powerful and useful tools

01:35:23.210 --> 01:35:24.490
that I've mentioned here on many times

01:35:24.490 --> 01:35:26.580
